# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gregory-bateson
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] In 2011, Haddon's 1898 *The Recordings of the Cambridge Anthropological Expedition to Torres Straits* were added to the National Film and Sound Archive of Australia's Sounds of Australia registry.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] The original recordings are housed at the British Library and many have been made available online.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Alfred Cort Haddon was born on 24 May 1855, near London, the elder son of John Haddon, the head of John Haddon & Co, a firm of printers and typefounders established in 1814.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He attended lectures at King's College London and taught zoology and geology at a girls' school in Dover, before entering Christ's College, Cambridge in 1875.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] At Cambridge, he studied zoology and became the friend of John Holland Rose (afterwards Harmsworth Professor of Naval History), whose sister he married in 1881.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Shortly after achieving his Master of Arts degree, he was appointed as Demonstrator in Zoology at Cambridge in 1879.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] For a time he studied marine biology in Naples.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] In 1880, he was appointed Professor of Zoology at the College of Science in Dublin.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] While there he founded the Dublin Field Club in 1885.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] His first publications were an *Introduction to the Study of Embryology* in 1887, and various papers on marine biology, which led to his expedition to the Torres Strait Islands to study coral reefs and marine zoology, and while thus engaged he first became attracted to anthropology.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] On his return home, he published many papers dealing with the indigenous people, urging the importance of securing all possible information about these and kindred peoples before they were overwhelmed by civilisation.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He advocated this in Cambridge, encouraged thereto by Thomas Henry Huxley, where he came to give lectures at the Anatomy School from 1894 to 1898.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Eventually, funds were raised to equip an expedition to the Torres Straits Islands to make a scientific study of the people, and Haddon was asked to assume the leadership.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] To assist him he succeeded in obtaining the help of Dr W.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Rivers, and in later years he used to say that he counted it his chief claim to fame that he had diverted Dr.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] The University of Cambridge later passed the wax cylinder recordings to the British Library.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] The main results of the expedition are published in *The Reports of the Cambridge Expedition to Torres Straits*.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon was convinced that the art objects collected would otherwise have been destroyed by Christian missionaries determined to eradicate the religious traditions and ceremonies of the native islanders.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Similar anthropological work, the recording of myths and legends from the Torres Strait Islands was coordinated by Margaret Lawrie during 1960–72.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He was appointed lecturer in ethnology in the University of Cambridge in 1900, and reader in 1909, a post from which he retired in 1926.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He was appointed advisory curator to the Horniman Museum in London in 1901.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon paid a third visit to New Guinea in 1914 returned during the First World War.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Accompanied by his daughter Kathleen Haddon (1888–1961), a zoologist, photographer and scholar of string-figures, the Haddons travelled along the Papuan coast from Daru to Aroma.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] While less discussed then his earlier work in the Torres Straits, this trip was influential in helping shape Haddon's later work on the distribution of material culture across New Guinea.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] The war effort had largely destroyed the study of anthropology at the university, however, and Haddon went to France to work for the Y.M.C.A.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] After the war, he renewed his constant struggle to establish a sound School of Anthropology in Cambridge.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] On his retirement Haddon was made honorary keeper of the rich collections from New Guinea which the Cambridge Museum possesses, and also wrote up the remaining parts of the Torres Straits Reports, which his busy teaching and administrative life had forced him to set aside.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] His help and counsel to younger men was then still more freely at their service, and as always he continually laid aside his own work to help them with theirs.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon was president of Section H (Anthropology) in the British Association meetings of 1902 and 1905.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He was the first to recognise the ethnological importance of string figures and tricks, known in England as "cats' cradles", but found all over the world as a pastime among native peoples.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He and Rivers invented a nomenclature and method of describing the process of making the different figures, and one of his daughters, Kathleen Rishbeth, became an expert authority on the subject.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] His main publications, besides those already mentioned, were: *Evolution in Art* (1895), *The Study of Man* (1898), *Head-hunters, Black, White and Brown* (1901), *The Races of Man* (1909; second, entirely rewritten, ed.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] He contributed to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, *Dictionary of National Biography*, and several articles to Hastings's *Encyclopaedia of Religion and Ethics*.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] A bibliography of his writings and papers runs to over 200 entries, even without his book reviews.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Though subsequently sidelined by Bronisław Malinowski, and the new paradigm of functionalism within anthropology, Haddon's work helped to support various anthropologists conducting then nascent fieldwork: A.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Brown in the Andaman Islands (1906–08), Gunnar Landtman on Kiwai in now Papua New Guinea (1910–12), Diamond Jenness (1911–12), R.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Marrett's student at the University of Oxford, as well as John Layard on Malakula, Vanuatu (1914–15), and to have Bronisław Malinowski stationed in Mailu and later the Trobriand Islands during World War 1.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon actively gave advice to missionaries, government officers, traders and anthropologists; in return, collecting information about New Guinea and elsewhere.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon's photographic archive and artefact collections can be found in the Museum of Anthropology and Archaeology in Cambridge University, while his papers are in the Cambridge University's Library's Special Collections.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon's wife, Fanny Elizabeth Haddon (née Rose), died in 1937, leaving a son and two daughters.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] Haddon's daughter Kathleen was a zoologist, photographer, and scholar of string-figures.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-c-haddon] She accompanied her father on a journey along the coast of New Guinea during his Torres Straits Expedition.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Deleuze and Guattari highly favor and criticize these figures, sometimes overlapping or "plugging" their statements, works, research, studies and fragments "into each other".
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In between are thirteen chapters, each dated non-linearly, sometimes precisely ("November 28, 1947: How Do You Make Yourself a Body Without Organs?"), sometimes less so ("10,000 B.C.: The Geology of Morals (Who Does the Earth Think It Is?)").
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In the sixth chapter, "Year Zero: Faciality" (*visagéité*), the notion of face is discussed as an "overcoding" of body, but also as being in dialectical tension with landscape (*paysagéité*).
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Like *Anti-Oedipus*, Deleuze and Guattari evaluate and criticize psychoanalysis: in the first two chapters, they discuss the work of Sigmund Freud, especially referring to the case histories of the Wolf Man and Little Hans.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In particular, focusing on child psychoanalysis, they remark that "children are Spinozists." Meanwhile, owing to their mode of literary analysis, *A Thousand Plateaus* also frequently discusses novels.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In "1874: Three Novellas, or "What Happened?"", they discuss Henry James' *In the Cage* (1898) and "The Story of the Abyss and the Spyglass" by Pierrette Fleutiaux, but they also evoke F.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Scott Fitzgerald's essay *The Crack-Up* (1945) (which Deleuze previously discussed in *The Logic of Sense*), because his depression and frustration in the essay is dramatized, and Deleuze's idea of the crack constitutes a narrativized breakdown.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] The works of Franz Kafka, Marcel Proust, Virginia Woolf, Henry Miller, D.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Lovecraft, Herman Melville and Chrétien de Troyes are also discussed, often in conjunction with the rhizome, becoming, faciality, and the regimes of signs.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Holland suggests that the work complicates the slogans and oppositions developed in its predecessor.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Whereas *Anti-Oedipus* created binaries such as molar/molecular, paranoid/schizophrenic, and deterritorialization/reterritorialization, *A Thousand Plateaus* shows how such distinctions are operations on the surface of a deeper field with more complicated and multidimensional dynamics.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In so doing, the book is less engaged with history than with topics like biology and geology.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Massumi writes that *A Thousand Plateaus* differs drastically in tone, content, and composition from *Anti-Oedipus*.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In his view, the schizoanalysis the authors practice is not so much a study of their "pathological condition", but a "positive process" that involves "inventive connection".
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] In 1997, the physicists Alan Sokal and Jean Bricmont asserted that the book contains many passages in which Deleuze and Guattari use "pseudo-scientific language".
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Digital media theorist Janet Murray links the work to the aesthetic of hypertext.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Gaming and electronic literature expert Espen Aarseth draws parallels between Deleuze and Guattari's idea of the rhizome and semiotician Umberto Eco's idea of the net.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Christopher Miller criticizes Deleuze and Guattari's use of "second-hand" anthropological sources without providing the reader with contextualization of the colonialist "mission" that led to their writing.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] Timothy Laurie says that this claim is inaccurate, but that Deleuze & Guattari should extend that same "rigor" to uncovering the political and economic entanglements which contextualize academic philosophy.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] The philosopher Manuel DeLanda, in *A New Philosophy of Society* (2006), adopts Deleuze's theory of assemblages, taken from *A Thousand Plateaus*.
[src:gregory-bateson/a-thousand-plateaus] According to military officers, Israel Defense Forces have taken influence and utilized concepts from *A Thousand Plateaus* in their conduct of genocide against Palestinians.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning, unlike deductive reasoning, yields a plausible conclusion but does not definitively verify it.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abductive conclusions do not eliminate uncertainty or doubt, which is expressed in terms such as "best available" or "most likely".
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] While inductive reasoning draws general conclusions that apply to many situations, abductive conclusions are confined to the particular observations in question.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In the 1990s, as computing power grew, the fields of law, computer science, and artificial intelligence research spurred renewed interest in the subject of abduction.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Diagnostic expert systems frequently employ abduction.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning allows deriving b from a only where b is a formal logical consequence of a .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In other words, deduction derives the consequences of the assumed.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Given the truth of the assumptions, a valid deduction guarantees the truth of the conclusion.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] For example, given that "Socrates is a man" ( $a_{1}$ ) and "All men are mortal" ( $a_{2}$ ), it follows that "Socrates is mortal" ( b ).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Inductive reasoning is the process of inferring some *general* principle b from a body of knowledge a , where b does not necessarily follow from a . a might give us very good reason to accept b but does not ensure b .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] For example, if all swans that a person has observed so far are white, they may infer a universal categorical proposition of the form *All swans are white*.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] They have good reason to believe the conclusion from the premise because it is the *best explanation* for their observations, but the truth of the conclusion is not guaranteed.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, it turns out that some swans are black.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abductive reasoning allows inferring a as an explanation of b .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] As a result of this inference, abduction allows the precondition a to be abducted from the consequence b .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Deductive reasoning and abductive reasoning differ in which end, left or right, of the proposition " a entails b " serves as the conclusion.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] For example, with deductive reasoning, knowing that it rained heavily during the night, you could deduce that the lawn will be wet in the morning without looking outside.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] With abductive reasoning, a couple leaving their house in the morning and seeing that their lawn is wet might abduce that it rained while they were asleep.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] This serves as a hypothesis that "best explains" their observation.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Given the many possible explanations for the lawn getting wet, their abduction does not establish certainty that it rained overnight, but it is still useful and can serve to orient them in their surroundings.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Despite many possible explanations for any physical process we observe, we tend to abduce a single explanation (or a few) for this process in the expectation that we can better orient ourselves in our surroundings and disregard some possibilities.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Properly used, abductive reasoning can be a useful source of priors in Bayesian statistics.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] One can understand abductive reasoning as inference to the best explanation, although the terms *abduction* and *inference to the best explanation* are not always used equivalently.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In logic, explanation is accomplished through the use of a logical theory T representing a domain and a set of observations O .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the process of deriving a set of explanations of O according to T and picking out one of those explanations.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In formal logic, O and E are assumed to be sets of literals.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Among the possible explanations E satisfying these two conditions, some other condition of minimality is usually imposed to avoid irrelevant facts (not contributing to the entailment of O ) being included in the explanations.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is then the process that picks out some member of E .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Criteria for picking out a member representing "the best" explanation include the simplicity, the prior probability, or the explanatory power of the explanation.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] A proof-theoretical abduction method for first-order classical logic based on the sequent calculus and a dual one, based on semantic tableaux (analytic tableaux) have been proposed.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The methods are sound and complete and work for full first-order logic, without requiring any preliminary reduction of formulae into normal forms.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] These methods have also been extended to modal logic.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abductive logic programming is a computational framework that extends normal logic programming with abduction.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] It separates the theory T into two components, one of which is a normal logic program, used to generate E by means of backward reasoning, the other of which is a set of integrity constraints, used to filter the set of candidate explanations.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] A different formalization of abduction is based on inverting the function that calculates the visible effects of the hypotheses.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Formally, we are given a set of hypotheses H and a set of manifestations M ; they are related by the domain knowledge, represented by a function e that takes as an argument a set of hypotheses and gives as a result the corresponding set of manifestations.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In other words, for every subset of the hypotheses $H'\subseteq H$ , their effects are known to be $e(H')$ .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is performed by finding a set $H'\subseteq H$ such that $M\subseteq e(H')$ .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In other words, abduction is performed by finding a set of hypotheses $H'$ such that their effects $e(H')$ include all observations M .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] A common assumption is that the effects of the hypotheses are independent, that is, for every $H'\subseteq H$ , it holds that $e(H')=\bigcup _{h\in H'}e(\{h\})$ .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] If this condition is met, abduction can be seen as a form of set covering.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abductive validation is the process of validating a given hypothesis through abductive reasoning.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] This can also be called reasoning through successive approximation.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Under this principle, an explanation is valid if it is the best possible explanation of a set of known data.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The best possible explanation is often defined in terms of simplicity and elegance (see Occam's razor).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Subjective logic generalises probabilistic logic by including degrees of epistemic uncertainty in the input arguments, i.e. instead of probabilities, the analyst can express arguments as subjective opinions.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction in subjective logic is thus a generalization of probabilistic abduction described above.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The input arguments in subjective logic are subjective opinions which can be binomial when the opinion applies to a binary variable or multinomial when it applies to an *n*-ary variable.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Assume the domains $\mathbf {X}$ and $\mathbf {Y}$ with respective variables X and Y , the set of conditional opinions $\omega _{X\mid Y}$ (i.e. one conditional opinion for each value y ), and the base rate distribution $a_{Y}$ .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Using these inverted conditionals together with the opinion $\omega _{X}$ subjective deduction denoted by the operator $\circledcirc$ can be used to abduce the marginal opinion $\omega _{Y\,{\overline {\|}}\,X}$ .
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The symbolic notation for subjective abduction is " ${\widetilde {\|}}$ ", and the operator itself is denoted as " ${\widetilde {\circledcirc }}$ ".
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The operator for the subjective Bayes' theorem is denoted " ${\widetilde {\phi \,}}$ ", and subjective deduction is denoted " $\circledcirc$ ".
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The advantage of using subjective logic abduction compared to probabilistic abduction is that both aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty about the input argument probabilities can be explicitly expressed and taken into account during the analysis.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] It is thus possible to perform abductive analysis in the presence of uncertain arguments, which naturally results in degrees of uncertainty in the output conclusions.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The idea that the simplest, most easily verifiable solution should be preferred over its more complicated counterparts is a very old one.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] To this point, George Pólya, in his treatise on problem-solving, makes reference to the following Latin truism: *simplex sigillum veri* (simplicity is the seal of truth).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The American philosopher Charles Sanders Peirce introduced abduction into modern logic.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Over the years he called such inference *hypothesis*, *abduction*, *presumption*, and *retroduction*.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] He considered it a topic in logic as a normative field in philosophy, not in purely formal or mathematical logic, and eventually as a topic also in economics of research.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] As two stages of the development, extension, etc., of a hypothesis in scientific inquiry, abduction and also induction are often collapsed into one overarching concept—the hypothesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] That is why, in the scientific method known from Galileo and Bacon, the abductive stage of hypothesis formation is conceptualized simply as induction.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Thus, in the twentieth century this collapse was reinforced by Karl Popper's explication of the hypothetico-deductive model, where the hypothesis is considered to be just "a guess" (in the spirit of Peirce).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] However, when the formation of a hypothesis is considered the result of a process it becomes clear that this "guess" has already been tried and made more robust in thought as a necessary stage of its acquiring the status of hypothesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Indeed, many abductions are rejected or heavily modified by subsequent abductions before they ever reach this stage.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Before 1900, Peirce treated abduction as the use of a known rule to explain an observation.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] For instance: it is a known rule that, if it rains, grass gets wet; so, to explain the fact that the grass on this lawn is wet, one *abduces* that it has rained.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can lead to false conclusions if other rules that might explain the observation are not taken into account—e.g. the grass could be wet from dew.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] This remains the common use of the term "abduction" in the social sciences and in artificial intelligence.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce consistently characterized it as the kind of inference that originates a hypothesis by concluding in an explanation, though an unassured one, for some very curious or surprising (anomalous) observation stated in a premise.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] As early as 1865 he wrote that all conceptions of cause and force are reached through hypothetical inference; in the 1900s he wrote that all explanatory content of theories is reached through abduction.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In other respects Peirce revised his view of abduction over the years.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In Peirce's *On the Natural Classification of Arguments* (1867), hypothetical inference always deals with a cluster of characters (call them *P′, P′′, P′′′,* etc.) known to occur at least whenever a certain character (*M*) occurs.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Note that categorical syllogisms have elements traditionally called middles, predicates, and subjects.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] For example: All *men* [middle] are *mortal* [predicate]; *Socrates* [subject] is a *man* [middle]; ergo *Socrates* [subject] is *mortal* [predicate]".
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Below, 'M' stands for a middle; 'P' for a predicate; 'S' for a subject.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that all deduction can be put into the form of the categorical syllogism Barbara (AAA-1).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In 1878, in *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis*, there is no longer a need for multiple characters or predicates in order for an inference to be hypothetical, although it is still helpful.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Moreover, Peirce no longer poses hypothetical inference as concluding in a *probable* hypothesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In the forms themselves, it is understood but not explicit that induction involves random selection and that hypothetical inference involves response to a "very curious circumstance".
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The forms instead emphasize the modes of inference as rearrangements of one another's propositions (without the bracketed hints shown below).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce long treated abduction in terms of induction from characters or traits (weighed, not counted like objects), explicitly so in his influential 1883 "A theory of probable inference", in which he returns to involving probability in the hypothetical conclusion.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Like *Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis* in 1878, it was widely read (see the historical books on statistics by Stephen Stigler), unlike his later amendments of his conception of abduction.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Today abduction remains most commonly understood as induction from characters and extension of a known rule to cover unexplained circumstances.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Sherlock Holmes used this method of reasoning in the stories of Arthur Conan Doyle, although Holmes refers to it as "deductive reasoning".
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In 1902 Peirce wrote that he now regarded the syllogistical forms and the doctrine of extension and comprehension (i.e., objects and characters as referenced by terms), as being less fundamental than he had earlier thought.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The hypothesis is framed, but not asserted, in a premise, then asserted as rationally suspectable in the conclusion.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Thus, as in the earlier categorical syllogistic form, the conclusion is formulated from some premise(s).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] But all the same the hypothesis consists more clearly than ever in a new or outside idea beyond what is known or observed.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Induction in a sense goes beyond observations already reported in the premises, but it merely amplifies ideas already known to represent occurrences, or tests an idea supplied by hypothesis; either way it requires previous abductions in order to get such ideas in the first place.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Induction seeks facts to test a hypothesis; abduction seeks a hypothesis to account for facts.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Note that the hypothesis ("A") could be of a rule.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] It need not even be a rule strictly necessitating the surprising observation ("C"), which needs to follow only as a "matter of course"; or the "course" itself could amount to some known rule, merely alluded to, and also not necessarily a rule of strict necessity.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce did not remain quite convinced about any such form as the categorical syllogistic form or the 1903 form.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In 1911, he wrote, "I do not, at present, feel quite convinced that any logical form can be assigned that will cover all 'Retroductions'.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] It is a method for fruitful clarification of conceptions by equating the meaning of a conception with the conceivable practical implications of its object's conceived effects.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce held that that is precisely tailored to abduction's purpose in inquiry, the forming of an idea that could conceivably shape informed conduct.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In various writings in the 1900s he said that the conduct of abduction (or retroduction) is governed by considerations of economy, belonging in particular to the economics of research.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] He regarded economics as a normative science whose analytic portion might be part of logical methodeutic (that is, theory of inquiry).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Logical critic, or logic proper, on validity or justifiability of inference, the conditions for true representation.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Critique of arguments in their various modes (deduction, induction, abduction).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Methodeutic, or speculative rhetoric, on the conditions for determination of interpretations.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Methodology of inquiry in its interplay of modes.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce had, from the start, seen the modes of inference as being coordinated together in scientific inquiry and, by the 1900s, held that hypothetical inference in particular is inadequately treated at the level of critique of arguments.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] To increase the assurance of a hypothetical conclusion, one needs to deduce implications about evidence to be found, predictions which induction can test through observation so as to evaluate the hypothesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] That is Peirce's outline of the scientific method of inquiry, as covered in his inquiry methodology, which includes pragmatism or, as he later called it, pragmaticism, the clarification of ideas in terms of their conceivable implications regarding informed practice.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Induction is inference through an *index* (a sign by factual connection); a sample is an index of the totality from which it is drawn.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Deduction is inference through a *symbol* (a sign by interpretive habit irrespective of resemblance or connection to its object).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] At the critical level Peirce examined the forms of abductive arguments (as discussed above), and came to hold that the hypothesis should economize explanation for plausibility in terms of the feasible and natural.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In 1908 Peirce described this plausibility in some detail.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The phrase "inference to the best explanation" (not used by Peirce but often applied to hypothetical inference) is not always understood as referring to the most simple and natural hypotheses (such as those with the fewest assumptions).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] However, in other senses of "best", such as "standing up best to tests", it is hard to know which is the best explanation to form, since one has not tested it yet.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Still, for Peirce, any justification of an abductive inference as "good" is not completed upon its formation as an argument (unlike with induction and deduction) and instead depends also on its methodological role and promise (such as its testability) in advancing inquiry.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Here, considerations such as probability, absent from the treatment of abduction at the critical level, come into play.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Peirce indicated that abductive reasoning is driven by the need for "economy in research"—the expected fact-based productivity of hypotheses, prior to deductive and inductive processes of verification.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] A key concept proposed by him in this regard is "uberty"—the expected fertility and pragmatic value of reasoning.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] This concept seems to be gaining support via association to the Free Energy Principle.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Gilbert Harman was a professor of philosophy at Princeton University.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Harman's 1965 account of the role of "inference to the best explanation" – inferring the existence of that which we need for the best explanation of observable phenomena – has been very influential.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Stephen Jay Gould, in answering the Omphalos hypothesis, claimed that only hypotheses that can be proved incorrect lie within the domain of science and only these hypotheses are good explanations of facts worth inferring to.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Applications in artificial intelligence include fault diagnosis, belief revision, and automated planning.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The most direct application of abduction is that of automatically detecting faults in systems: given a theory relating faults with their effects and a set of observed effects, abduction can be used to derive sets of faults that are likely to be the cause of the problem.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In medicine, abduction can be seen as a component of clinical evaluation and judgment.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The Internist-I diagnostic system, the first AI system that covered the field of Internal Medicine, used abductive reasoning to converge on the most likely causes of a set of patient symptoms that it acquired through an interactive dialog with an expert user.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction can also be used to model automated planning.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Given a logical theory relating action occurrences with their effects (for example, a formula of the event calculus), the problem of finding a plan for reaching a state can be modeled as the problem of abducting a set of literals implying that the final state is the goal state.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In intelligence analysis, analysis of competing hypotheses and Bayesian networks, probabilistic abductive reasoning is used extensively.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Similarly in medical diagnosis and legal reasoning, the same methods are being used, although there have been many examples of errors, especially caused by the base rate fallacy and the prosecutor's fallacy.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Belief revision, the process of adapting beliefs in view of new information, is another field in which abduction has been applied.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The main problem of belief revision is that the new information may be inconsistent with the prior web of beliefs, while the result of the incorporation cannot be inconsistent.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The process of updating the web of beliefs can be done by the use of abduction: once an explanation for the observation has been found, integrating it does not generate inconsistency.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In 1992 Peter Gärdenfors presented a paper which contained a brief survey of the area of belief revision and its relation to updating of logical databases, and explores the relationship between belief revision and nonmonotonic logic.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] This use of abduction is not straightforward, as adding propositional formulae to other propositional formulae can only make inconsistencies worse.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Instead, abduction is done at the level of the ordering of preference of the possible worlds.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Preference models use fuzzy logic or utility models.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In the philosophy of science, abduction has been the key inference method to support scientific realism, and much of the debate about scientific realism is focused on whether abduction is an acceptable method of inference.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In historical linguistics, abduction during language acquisition is often taken to be an essential part of processes of language change such as reanalysis and analogy.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In applied linguistics research, abductive reasoning is starting to be used as an alternative explanation to inductive reasoning, in recognition of anticipated outcomes of qualitative inquiry playing a role in shaping the direction of analysis.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] It is defined as "The use of an unclear premise based on observations, pursuing theories to try to explain it" (Rose et al., 2020, p.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is used as the mechanism for getting from art to agency.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] That is, abduction can explain how works of art inspire a *sensus communis:* the commonly held views shared by members that characterize a given society.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction is the answer to this conundrum because the tentative nature of the abduction concept (Peirce likened it to guessing) means that not only can it operate outside of any pre-existing framework, but moreover, it can actually intimate the existence of a framework.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] As Gell reasons in his analysis, the physical existence of the artwork prompts the viewer to perform an abduction that imbues the artwork with intentionality.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] A statue of a goddess, for example, in some senses actually becomes the goddess in the mind of the beholder; and represents not only the form of the deity but also her intentions (which are adduced from the feeling of her very presence).
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Therefore, through abduction, Gell claims that art can have the kind of agency that plants the seeds that grow into cultural myths.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] The power of agency is the power to motivate actions and inspire ultimately the shared understanding that characterizes any given society.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In formal methods, logic is used to specify and prove properties of computer programs.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] Abduction has been used in mechanized reasoning tools to increase the level of automation of the proof activity.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] It led to a program-proof startup company, which was acquired by Facebook, and the Infer program analysis tool, which led to thousands of bugs being prevented in industrial codebases.
[src:gregory-bateson/abductive-reasoning] In addition to inference of function preconditions, abduction has been used to automate inference of invariants for program loops, inference of specifications of unknown code, and in synthesis of the programs themselves.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT holds that social forces do not exist in themselves, and therefore cannot be used to explain social phenomena.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Instead, strictly empirical analysis should be undertaken to "describe" rather than "explain" social activity.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Only after this can one introduce the concept of social forces, and only as an abstract theoretical concept, not something which genuinely exists in the world.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Although it is best known for its controversial insistence on the capacity of nonhumans to act or participate in systems or networks or both, ANT is also associated with forceful critiques of conventional and critical sociology.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Developed by science and technology studies (STS) scholars Michel Callon, Madeleine Akrich and Bruno Latour, the sociologist John Law, and others, it can more technically be described as a "material-semiotic" method.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This means that it maps relations that are simultaneously material (between things) and semiotic (between concepts).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It assumes that many relations are both material and semiotic.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The theory demonstrates that everything in the social and natural worlds, human and nonhuman, interacts in shifting networks of relationships without any other elements out of the networks.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT challenges many traditional approaches by defining nonhumans as actors equal to humans.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This claim provides a new perspective when applying the theory in practice.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Broadly speaking, ANT is a constructivist approach in that it avoids essentialist explanations of events or innovations (i.e.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT explains a successful theory by understanding the combinations and interactions of elements that make it successful, rather than saying it is true and the others are false).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Likewise, it is not a cohesive theory in itself.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Rather, ANT functions as a strategy that assists people in being sensitive to terms and the often unexplored assumptions underlying them.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It is distinguished from many other STS and sociological network theories for its distinct material-semiotic approach.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT was first developed at the Centre de Sociologie de l'Innovation (CSI) of the École nationale supérieure des mines de Paris in the early 1980s by staff (Michel Callon, Madeleine Akrich, Bruno Latour) and visitors (including John Law).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT appears to reflect many of the preoccupations of French post-structuralism, and in particular a concern with non-foundational and multiple material-semiotic relations.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] At the same time, it was much more firmly embedded in English-language academic traditions than most post-structuralist-influenced approaches.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Its grounding in (predominantly English) science and technology studies was reflected in an intense commitment to the development of theory through qualitative empirical case-studies.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Its links with largely US-originated work on large technical systems were reflected in its willingness to analyse large scale technological developments in an even-handed manner to include political, organizational, legal, technical and scientific factors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The "state of the art" of ANT in the late 1980s is well-described in Latour's 1987 text, *Science in Action*.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] From about 1990 onwards, ANT started to become popular as a tool for analysis in a range of fields beyond STS.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It was picked up and developed by authors in parts of organizational analysis, informatics, health studies, geography, sociology, anthropology, archaeology, feminist studies, technical communication, and economics.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] As of 2008, ANT is a widespread, if controversial, range of material-semiotic approaches for the analysis of heterogeneous relations.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In part because of its popularity, it is interpreted and used in a wide range of alternative and sometimes incompatible ways.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] There is no orthodoxy in current ANT, and different authors use the approach in substantially different ways.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Some authors talk of "after-ANT" to refer to "successor projects" blending together different problem-focuses with those of ANT.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] An actor (actant) is that which acts and causes action.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It implies no motivation of human individual actors nor of humans in general.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] An actant can literally be anything provided it is granted to be the source of action.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In another word, an actor, in this circumstance, is considered as any entity that does things.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For example, in the "Pasteur Network", microorganisms are not inert, they cause unsterilized materials to ferment while leaving behind sterilized materials not affected.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] If they took other actions, that is, if they did not cooperate with Pasteur – if they did not take action (at least according to Pasteur's intentions) – then Pasteur's story may be a bit different.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It is in this sense that Latour can refer to microorganisms as actors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Under the framework of ANT, the principle of generalized symmetry requires all entities must be described in the same terms before a network is considered.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Any differences between entities are generated in the network of relations, and do not exist before any network is applied.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Human normally refers to human beings and their human behaviors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Traditionally, nonhuman entities are creatures including plants, animals, geology, and natural forces, as well as a collective human making of arts, languages.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In ANT, nonhuman covers multiple entities including things, objects, animals, natural phenomena, material structures, transportation devices, texts, and economic goods.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] But nonhuman actors do not cover entities such as humans, supernatural beings, and other symbolic objects in nature.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] As the term implies, the actor-network is the central concept in ANT.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The term "network" is somewhat problematic in that it, as Latour notes, has a number of unwanted connotations.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Firstly, it implies that what is described takes the shape of a network, which is not necessarily the case.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Secondly, it implies "transportation without deformation," which, in ANT, is not possible since any actor-network involves a vast number of translations.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Actor–network theory tries to explain how material–semiotic networks come together to act as a whole; the clusters of actors involved in creating meaning are both material and semiotic.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] As a part of this it may look at explicit strategies for relating different elements together into a network so that they form an apparently coherent whole.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] These networks are potentially transient, existing in a constant making and re-making.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This means that relations need to be repeatedly "performed" or the network will dissolve.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] They also assume that networks of relations are not intrinsically coherent, and may indeed contain conflicts.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Social relations, in other words, are only ever in process, and must be performed continuously.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The Pasteur story that was mentioned above introduced the patterned network of diverse materials, which is called the idea of 'heterogenous networks'.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The basic idea of patterned network is that human is not the only factor or contributor in the society, or in any social activities and networks.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Thus, the network composes machines, animals, things, and any other objects.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For those nonhuman actors, it might be hard for people to imagine their roles in the network.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For example, say two people, Jacob and Mike, are speaking through texts.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Within the current technology, they are able to communicate with each other without seeing each other in person.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Therefore, when typing or writing, the communication is basically not mediated by either of them, but instead by a network of objects, like their computers or cell phones.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] If taken to its logical conclusion, then, nearly any actor can be considered merely a sum of other, smaller actors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] A car is an example of a complicated system.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It contains many electronic and mechanical components, all of which are essentially hidden from view to the driver, who simply deals with the car as a single object.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This effect is known as *punctualisation*, and is similar to the idea of encapsulation in object-oriented programming.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] When an actor network breaks down, the punctualisation effect tends to cease as well.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In the automobile example above, a non-working engine would cause the driver to become aware of the car as a collection of parts rather than just a vehicle capable of transporting him or her from place to place.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This can also occur when elements of a network act contrarily to the network as a whole.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In his book *Pandora's Hope*, Latour likens depunctualization to the opening of a black box.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] When closed, the box is perceived simply as a box, although when it is opened all elements inside it become visible.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Central to ANT is the concept of translation which is sometimes referred to as **sociology of translation**, in which innovators attempt to create a *forum*, a central network in which all the actors agree that the network is worth building and defending.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] **Interessement**: A series of procedures used by the researchers to bind the other actors to the parts that had been assigned to them in that program.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] **Enrollment**: A collection of tactics used by the researchers to define and connect the numerous roles they had assigned to others.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] **Mobilisation**: The researchers utilized a series of approaches to ensure that ostensible spokespeople for various key collectivities were appropriately able to represent those collectivities and were not deceived by the latter.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Also important to the notion is the role of network objects in helping to smooth out the translation process by creating equivalencies between what would otherwise be very challenging people, organizations or conditions to mesh together.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Bruno Latour spoke about this particular task of objects in his work *Reassembling the Social*.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For the rethinking of social relations as networks, Latour mobilizes a concept from Michel Serres and expands on it in order “to locate the position of these strange new hybrids”.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Actor–network theory refers to these creations as *tokens* or *quasi-objects* which are passed between actors within the network.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] As the token is increasingly transmitted or passed through the network, it becomes increasingly punctualized and also increasingly reified.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] When the token is decreasingly transmitted, or when an actor fails to transmit the token (e.g., the oil pump breaks), punctualization and reification are decreased as well.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Although it is called a "theory", ANT does not usually explain "why" a network takes the form that it does.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Rather, ANT is a way of thoroughly exploring the relational ties within a network (which can be a multitude of different things).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] As Latour notes, "explanation does not follow from description; it is description taken that much further." It is not, in other words, a theory "of" anything, but rather a method, or a "how-to book" as Latour puts it.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The approach is related to other versions of material-semiotics (notably the work of philosophers Gilles Deleuze, Michel Foucault, and feminist scholar Donna Haraway).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It can also be seen as a way of being faithful to the insights of ethnomethodology and its detailed descriptions of how common activities, habits and procedures sustain themselves.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Similarities between ANT and symbolic interactionist approaches such as the newer forms of grounded theory like situational analysis, exist, although Latour objects to such a comparison.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Although ANT is mostly associated with studies of science and technology and with the sociology of science, it has been making steady progress in other fields of sociology as well.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT is adamantly empirical, and as such yields useful insights and tools for sociological inquiry in general.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT has been deployed in studies of identity and subjectivity, urban transportation systems, and passion and addiction.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It also makes steady progress in political and historical sociology.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The distinction between intermediaries and mediators is key to ANT sociology.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Intermediaries are entities which make no difference (to some interesting state of affairs which we are studying) and so can be ignored.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] They transport the force of some other entity more or less without transformation and so are fairly uninteresting.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Mediators are entities which multiply difference and so should be the object of study.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Their outputs cannot be predicted by their inputs.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] From an ANT point of view sociology has tended to treat too much of the world as intermediaries.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For instance, a sociologist might take silk and nylon as intermediaries, holding that the former "means", "reflects", or "symbolises" the upper classes and the latter the lower classes.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In such a view the real world silk–nylon difference is irrelevant– presumably many other material differences could also, and do also, transport this class distinction.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] But taken as mediators these fabrics would have to be engaged with by the analyst in their specificity: the internal real-world complexities of silk and nylon suddenly appear relevant, and are seen as actively constructing the ideological class distinction which they once merely reflected.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For the committed ANT analyst, social things—like class distinctions in taste in the silk and nylon example, but also groups and power—must constantly be constructed or performed anew through complex engagements with complex mediators.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] There is no stand-alone social repertoire lying in the background to be reflected off, expressed through, or substantiated in, interactions (as in an intermediary conception).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Bruno Latour's articulation of reflexivity in Actor-Network Theory (ANT) reframes it as an opportunity rather than a problem.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] His argument addresses the limitations of reflexivity as traditionally conceived in relativist epistemologies and replaces it with a pragmatic, relational approach tied to ANT's broader principles.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Latour argues that the observer is merely one actor among many within the network, eliminating the problem of reflexivity as a paradox of status.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Reflexivity instead emerges through the tangible work of navigating and translating between networks, requiring the observer to engage actively, like any other actor, in the labour of connection and translation.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This grounded form of reflexivity enhances the observer's role as a "world builder" and reinforces ANT's emphasis on the relational and dynamic nature of knowledge creation.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The belief that neither a human nor a nonhuman is pure, in the sense that neither is human or nonhuman in an absolute sense, but rather beings created via interactions between the two.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Humans are thus regarded as quasi-subjects, while nonhumans are regarded as quasi-objects.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Actor–network theory has become increasingly prominent within the discipline of international relations and political science.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Empirically, IR scholars have drawn on insights from ANT in order to study phenomena including political violences like the use of torture and drones, piracy and maritime governance, and garbage.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The actor–network theory can also be applied to design, using a perspective that is not simply limited to an analysis of an object's structure.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] From the ANT viewpoint, design is seen as a series of features that account for a social, psychological, and economical world.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT argues that objects are designed to shape human action and mold or influence decisions.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In this way, the objects' design serves to mediate human relationships and can even impact our morality, ethics, and politics.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The literary critic Rita Felski has argued that ANT offers the fields of literary criticism and cultural studies vital new modes of interpreting and engaging with literary texts.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] She claims that Latour's model has the capacity to allow "us to wiggle out of the straitjacket of suspicion," and to offer meaningful solutions to the problems associated with critique.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The theory has been crucial to her formulation of postcritique.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In the study of Christianity by anthropologists, the ANT has been employed in a variety of ways of understanding how humans interact with nonhuman actors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Some have been critical of the field of Anthropology of Religion in its tendency to presume that God is not a social actor.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The ANT is used to problematize the role of God, as a nonhuman actor, and speak of how They affect religious practice.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Others have used the ANT to speak of the structures and placements of religious buildings, especially in cross-cultural contexts, which can see architecture as agents making God's presence tangible.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT has been considered more than just a theory, but also a methodology.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In fact, ANT is a useful method that can be applied in different studies.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Moreover, with the development of the digital communication, ANT now is popular in being applied in science field like IS research.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In addition, it widen the horizon of researchers from arts field as well.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT is a big influencer in the development of design.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In the past, researchers or scholars from design field mainly view the world as a human interactive situation.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] No matter what design we [who?] applied, it is for human's action.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] However, the idea of ANT now applies into design principle, where design starts to be viewed as a connector.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] As the view of design itself has changed, the design starts to be considered more important in daily lives.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Scholars [who?] analyze how design shapes, connects, reflects, interacts our daily activities.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT has also been widely applied in museums.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT proposes that it is difficult to discern the 'hard' from the 'soft' components of the apparatus in curatorial practice; that the object 'in progress' of being curated is slick and difficult to separate from the setting of the experiment or the experimenter's identity.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In recent years, actor-network theory has gained a lot of traction, and a growing number of IS academics are using it explicitly in their research.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Despite the fact that these applications vary greatly, all of the scholars cited below agree that the theory provides new notions and ideas for understanding the socio-technical character of information systems.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Bloomfield present an intriguing case study of the development of a specific set of resource management information systems in the UK National Health Service, and they evaluate their findings using concepts from actor-network theory.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The actor-network approach does not prioritize social or technological aspects, which mirrors the situation in the case study, where arguments about social structures and technology are intertwined within actors' discourse as they try to persuade others to align with their own goals.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] The research emphasizes the interpretative flexibility of information technology and systems, in the sense that seemingly similar systems produce drastically different outcomes in different locales as a result of the specific translation and network-building processes that occurred.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] They show how the boundary between the technological and the social, as well as the link between them, is the topic of constant battles and trials of strength in the creation of facts, rather than taking technology for granted.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] There are at least four contributions of nonhumans as actors in their ANT positions.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Nonhuman actors can be considered as mediators.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] On the one hand, nonhumans could constantly modify relations between actors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] On the other hand, nonhumans share the same features with other actors not solely as means for human actors.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In this circumstance, nonhuman actors impact human interactions.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] It either creates an atmosphere for humans to agree with each other, or lead to conflict as the mediators.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Nonhuman actors can be considered as members of moral and political associations.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] For example, noise is a nonhuman actor if the topic is applied to actor-network theory.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Noise is the criteria for humans to regulate themselves to morality, and subject to the limitations inherent in some legal rules for its political effects.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] After nonhumans are visible actors through their associations with morality and politics, these collectives become inherently regulative principles in social networks.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Nonhuman actors can be considered as gatherings.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Alike nonhumans' impacts on morality and politics, they could gather actors from other times and spaces.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Interacted with variable ontologies, times, spaces, and durability, nonhumans exert subtle influences within a network.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Some critics have argued that research based on ANT perspectives remains entirely descriptive and fails to provide explanations for social processes.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] ANT—like comparable social scientific methods—requires judgement calls from the researcher as to which actors are important within a network and which are not.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Critics argue that the importance of particular actors cannot be determined in the absence of "out-of-network" criteria, such as is a logically proven fact about deceptively coherent systems given Gödel's incompleteness theorems.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Similarly, others argue that actor-networks risk degenerating into endless chains of association (six degrees of separation—we are all networked to one another).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Other research perspectives such as social constructionism, social shaping of technology, social network theory, normalization process theory, and diffusion of innovations theory are held to be important alternatives to ANT approaches.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Key early criticism came from other members of the STS community, in particular the "Epistemological Chicken" debate between Collins and Yearley with responses from Latour and Callon as well as Woolgar.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In an article in *Science as Practice and Culture*, sociologist Harry Collins and his co-writer Steven Yearley argue that the ANT approach is a step backwards towards the positivist and realist positions held by early theory of science.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Collins and Yearley accused ANTs approach of collapsing into an endless relativist regress.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Whittle and organization studies professor André Spicer note that "ANT has also sought to move beyond deterministic models that trace organizational phenomena back to powerful individuals, social structures, hegemonic discourses or technological effects.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Accordingly, ANT can be seen as an attempt to re-introduce Whig history into science and technology studies; like the myth of the heroic inventor, ANT can be seen as an attempt to explain successful innovators by saying only that they were successful.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Actor–network theory insists on the capacity of nonhumans to be actors or participants in networks and systems.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Critics including figures such as Langdon Winner maintain that such properties as intentionality fundamentally distinguish humans from animals or from "things" (see Activity Theory).
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Wiebe Bijker has responded to this criticism by stating that the amorality of ANT is not a necessity.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] Moral and political positions are possible, but one must first describe the network before taking up such positions.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] This position has been further explored by Stuart Shapiro who contrasts ANT with the history of ecology, and argues that research decisions are moral rather than methodological, but this moral dimension has been sidelined.
[src:gregory-bateson/actor-network-theory] In a workshop called "On Recalling ANT", Latour *himself* stated that there are four things wrong with actor-network theory: "actor", "network", "theory" and the hyphen.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial archaeology involves interpretation and image analysis of photographic and other kinds of images in field research to understand archaeological features, sites, and landscapes.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] It enables exploration and examination of context and large land areas, on a scale unparalleled by other archaeological methods.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The AARG (Aerial Archaeology Research Group) boasts that "more archaeological features have been found worldwide through aerial photography than by any other means of survey".
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial archaeological survey combines data collection and data analysis.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The umbrella term "aerial images" includes traditional aerial photographs, satellite images, multispectral data (which captures image data within specific wavelength ranges across the electromagnetic spectrum) and hyperspectral data (similar to multispectral data, but more detailed).
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] A vast bank of aerial images exists, with parts freely available online or at specialist libraries.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These are often vertical images taken for area surveys by aircraft or satellite (not necessarily for archaeological reasons).
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Each year a small number of aerial images are taken by archaeologists during prospective surveys.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The origins of aerial photography, which led to the rise of aerial archaeology, began in the mid-19th century with early experiments in capturing landscapes from above.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The French photographer Nadar (Gaspard-Félix Tournachon), who is credited with taking the first aerial photograph from a balloon in 1858 over the outskirts of Paris.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In America, a man named James Wallace Black, in 1860, became the first person to successfully take aerial photographs from a hot air balloon over Boston.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Around the same time, Thaddeus Lowe, a scientist and aeronaut, also used balloons for military reconnaissance during the American Civil War.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In the years leading up to the First World War, several early attempts were made to use aerial photography for archaeological purposes, though they often faced significant technical and practical challenges.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] One of the earliest figures involved in this effort was Sir Henry Wellcome, a British–American pharmaceutical entrepreneur and philanthropist.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In the early 1900s, Wellcome financed several archaeological expeditions in Sudan, where he employed aerial photography using a box kite to document excavations in Jebel Moya, Sudan.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Nevertheless, while the products of these efforts proved the potential value of aerial photographs for archaeological research, these early attempts to obtain usable photographs fell short.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Camera technology of the time was insufficient, let alone the erstwhile methods for getting cameras into the air.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The outbreak of World War I marked a critical turning point in the development of aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] British and Belgian air forces pioneered the use of aerial photography for reconnaissance as early as 1914, marking the beginning of a systematic approach to aerial observations.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial photography advanced rapidly due to its essential role in military reconnaissance.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Both the Allies and Central Powers relied heavily on aerial photographs to map enemy positions and monitor battlefield activity.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] It was during this time that aerial photography techniques improved dramatically, particularly in terms of camera technology, altitude, and photographic film quality.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The use of specialized reconnaissance aircraft, which were equipped with advanced cameras, allowed for the collection of high-resolution images on a scale and precision previously unattainable.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Although aerial photography during the war was primarily a military tool, its application to archaeology was soon recognized.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The thousands of aerial photographs captured over Europe revealed previously unknown archaeological features, such as crop marks, that were visible from the air but invisible from the ground.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These images, primarily intended for military strategy, revealed unexpected archaeological features, especially in Europe.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] This discovery highlighted the potential of aerial photography not just for military purposes but also for archaeological discovery and documentation.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] After the war, many of the techniques and technologies developed during the conflict were adopted by archaeologists.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Figures like English archaeologist O.G.S.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Crawford, who is widely considered the "father of aerial archaeology," were instrumental in applying wartime advances to peacetime archaeological research.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Crawford recognized the potential of aerial photography for archaeological research and conducted extensive surveys of the English landscape from the air.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] He published numerous articles and books on the subject, laying the foundation for the development of aerial archaeology as a scientific discipline.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Crawford's systematic use of aerial photography in the 1920s marked the beginning of modern aerial archaeology, building on the foundations laid by earlier pioneers and the technological leaps made during the war.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In the 1920s, Osbert Guy Stanhope Crawford emerged as a key figure in the development of aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Crawford recognized the potential of aerial photography for systematically documenting archaeological sites.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] His work in Britain and the Middle East demonstrated that aerial surveys could reveal features such as crop marks and soil disturbances that were undetectable from ground level.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] His pioneering efforts helped establish aerial archaeology as a legitimate and essential method within the broader field of archaeological research.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Allen was an English engineer who, after learning of the work Crawford was doing, he was inspired to use his own airplane around Southern England, taking photographs of the landscape.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] His work in documenting prehistoric landscapes and Roman roads in England marked a significant advancement in the application of aerial methods for archaeological surveys.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Following the Second World War, advancements in aerial photography and imaging techniques significantly broadened the scope of aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The introduction of infrared photography and multispectral imaging enabled archaeologists to detect subtle variations in vegetation and soil, allowing for the identification of buried structures that would otherwise remain hidden.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These technological innovations made it possible to conduct more detailed and accurate surveys, further enhancing the effectiveness of aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In the post-war period, aerial archaeology expanded beyond Europe, becoming an invaluable tool for researchers working in regions with vast and difficult-to-access landscapes, such as the Americas, Africa, and Asia.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In these areas, aerial surveys uncovered ancient civilizations and revealed the locations of significant archaeological sites, many of which had been previously unknown.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The ability to survey large areas quickly and efficiently made aerial archaeology a critical tool for understanding diverse archaeological landscapes across the globe.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In recent years, the advent of drones, or unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), has revolutionized aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Drones offer greater flexibility and lower operational costs compared to traditional crewed aircraft.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] With the ability to capture high-resolution images and access areas that are otherwise difficult to reach, drones have become an essential tool for modern archaeological surveys.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The increased use of drones has made aerial archaeology more accessible to a broader range of researchers and has led to more frequent and detailed studies of archaeological landscapes.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Technological advancements such as LiDAR (Light Detection and Ranging) and photogrammetry have further enhanced aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] LiDAR, in particular, is capable of penetrating dense vegetation to reveal features hidden beneath forest canopies, making it a valuable tool for studying heavily forested regions.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Photogrammetry, which allows for the creation of precise 3D models of archaeological sites, has enabled researchers to document and analyze sites with increased speed and accuracy.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Together, these technologies have expanded the potential of aerial archaeology, allowing for more detailed and comprehensive analyses of archaeological sites.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial archaeology plays a crucial role in discovering new archaeological sites and mapping their extent.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] By providing a bird's-eye view, aerial images can reveal subtle features and patterns that are often invisible from the ground.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial images provide a wealth of information for identifying and recording archaeological features.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] By carefully analyzing aerial images, archaeologists can identify, document, and interpret a wide range of archaeological features, providing valuable insights into past human activities and settlement patterns.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial photographs provide the foundation for creating accurate and detailed site plans and maps.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These site plans and maps are essential for documenting archaeological sites, planning excavations, and managing cultural heritage resources.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] They provide a valuable record of the site's extent, features, and spatial context, aiding in interpretation and future research.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Photography is the most common method used in aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Archaeologists use specialized cameras and lenses to capture high-resolution images of the ground from aircraft or drones.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The choice between oblique and vertical photography depends on the specific research questions and the characteristics of the site being investigated.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Often, archaeologists use a combination of both techniques to gain a comprehensive understanding of the archaeological record.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Certain archaeological features are more visible from the air than on the ground due to their nature.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] A key concept behind interpretation in aerial archaeology is that formation processes affect site features differently after abandonment.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] For a site to be detected by a remote sensing method, one would expect alterations to the soil or subsoil e.g. ditches, pits, banks, mounds, walls etc. which often are visible in relief.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] For a three-dimensional effect, an overlapping pair of vertical photographs, taken from slightly offset positions, can be viewed stereoscopically.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Beyond traditional aerial photography, archaeologists use a range of remote sensing techniques to investigate sites without physical excavation.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These methods involve collecting data from a distance using specialized sensors that detect and record different forms of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] This information can reveal subsurface features, variations in vegetation, and other archaeological clues hidden from the naked eye.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The **NASA LANDSAT series** (satellite observations) are often used in aerial archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Lidar (light detection and ranging) aka ALS (airborne laser scanning) uses laser scanner pulses to measure the distance to the ground and other objects.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] By emitting thousands of pulses per second and recording the time it takes for them to return to the sensor, LiDAR creates highly accurate 3D models of the Earth's surface.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In places yet to be documented (or where maps are considered confidential), satellite imagery is vital to providing base maps for excavation.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Satellite imagery offers a broad perspective, covering vast areas and providing valuable data for regional studies and landscape archaeology.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] One of the useful resources for accessing satellite imagery is Google Earth.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] This platform includes a range of different satellite and aerial images, such as the NASA LANDSAT series, Ikonos, QuickBird, GeoEye alongside more.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The Cold War **CORONA** satellite photographs have been used extensively for base maps and provisional interpretation.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In contrast to other imagery, CORONA uses two images of the same feature to create a stereoscopic view, which can allow for more accurate examination and interpretation in 3D.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Thermal imaging captures infrared radiation emitted by objects, revealing differences in temperature and emissivity.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These advanced imaging techniques capture data across a wide range of the electromagnetic spectrum, going beyond the visible light captured by traditional cameras.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] For data analysis, aerial images must be analyzed and interpreted using specialized skill-sets.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] This includes an understanding of formation processes as well as contemporary history and landscape history.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Often aerial archaeology will be carried out using computer programmed (such as GIS) aiding interpretation.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The raw data collected through aerial photography and remote sensing requires careful processing and interpretation to extract meaningful archaeological information.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Photogrammetry is a technique for creating 3D models from overlapping photographs.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] By analyzing the different perspectives captured in multiple images, specialized software can reconstruct the geometry of the scene.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Geographic Information Systems (GIS) are essential tools in modern archaeology, providing a powerful platform for managing, analyzing, and visualizing spatial data.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Raw aerial images often require enhancement to improve their clarity and highlight archaeological features.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] These image enhancement and analysis techniques are crucial for extracting meaningful information from aerial imagery, allowing archaeologists to identify subtle archaeological features and interpret their significance within the broader landscape.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Aerial archaeology, specifically Lidar, was used to study the site, a Mayan city in Belize, dated to 550–900 AD.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Archaeologists Arlen and Diane Chase, from the University of Central Florida, worked for 25 years in the dense tropical rainforest, managing to map 23 km2 (8.9 sq mi) of settlement.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] At the end of the dry season of 2009, they embarked on four continuous days of LiDAR flying, followed by three weeks of analysis by remote sensing experts.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] This allowed them to surpass the results of the prior 25 years, revealing over 177 km2 (68 sq mi) of city—a far larger area than expected.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Furthermore, the landscape was modelled in 3D, leading to the discovery of possible new sites such as "ruins, agricultural terraces and stone causeways" (to be investigated further for a greater understanding).
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] We can thus see the impressive effect aerial methods can have on streamlining archaeological survey, and pushing the limits of what is possible.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Homs, Syria provides an example of how different types of satellite imagery can be used in combination.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The site is based in an area notorious for its difficulties surrounding archaeological survey, as the diversity of terrain makes the detection of archaeological sites difficult.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] As a result, Homs is a perfect candidate for aerial reconnaissance.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Modern agriculture often obscures remains through practices such as deep ploughing (which removes many levees and low-lying sites from the archaeological record).
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Furthermore, vegetation of different types/densities frequently disguises sites, impeding site visibility.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The Homs projects combined the usage of CORONA, LANDSAT, Ikonos, and QuickBird imagery to observe "long-term human and environmental interactions" and, more broadly, to assess the landscape, over an area of 630 square kilometres that had no prior database of remains or aerial photography.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Through fieldwork, the different applications and abilities of these satellite imagery techniques were revealed, highlighting the importance of using multiple methods of archaeological investigation together.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] The LANDSAT imagery fell short when used for site detection and mapping, due to its lower resolution compared to Quickbird and IKONOS, but was most successful at characterizing the environment and visualizing rates of change.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] CORONA imagery successfully detected single-period sites, which could not be detected by IKONOS.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] Furthermore, CORONA imagery assisted in exposing ancient field systems, and crop marks within fields, revealing early watercourses.
[src:gregory-bateson/aerial-archaeology] In this instance, visual detection and interpretation of satellite imagery proved more useful than processing LANDSAT imagery.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Born in Warsaw, Vistula Country, which was then part of the Russian Empire, Korzybski belonged to an aristocratic Polish family whose members had worked as mathematicians, scientists, and engineers for generations.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He learned the Polish language at home and the Russian language in schools, and having a French and German governess, he became fluent in four languages as a child.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Korzybski studied engineering at the Warsaw University of Technology.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] During the First World War (1914–1918) Korzybski served as an intelligence officer in the Russian Army.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] After being wounded in a leg and suffering other injuries, he moved to North America in 1916 (first to Canada, then to the United States) to coordinate the shipment of artillery to Russia.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He also lectured to Polish-American audiences about the conflict, promoting the sale of war bonds.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] After the war he decided to remain in the United States, becoming a naturalized citizen in 1940.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He met Mira Edgerly, a painter of portraits on ivory, shortly after the 1918 Armistice; They married in January 1919; the marriage lasted until his death.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Dutton published Korzybski's first book, *Manhood of Humanity*, in 1921.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] In this work he proposed and explained in detail a new theory of humankind: mankind as a "time-binding" class of life (humans perform time binding by the transmission of knowledge and abstractions through time which become accreted in cultures).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] In 1925 and 1926, Korzybski observed psychiatric patients at St.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Elizabeth's hospital in D.C. under the supervision of William Alanson White.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Korzybski's work culminated in the initiation of a discipline that he named general semantics (GS).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] This should not be confused with semantics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] The basic principles of general semantics, which include time-binding, are described in the book *Science and Sanity*, published in 1933.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] In 1938, Korzybski founded the Institute of General Semantics in Chicago.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] The post-World War II housing shortage in Chicago cost him the institute's building lease, so in 1946 he moved the institute to Lakeville, Connecticut, U.S., where he directed it until his death in 1950.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Korzybski maintained that humans are limited in what they know by (1) the structure of their nervous systems, and (2) the structure of their languages.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Humans cannot experience the world directly, but only through their "abstractions" (nonverbal impressions or "gleanings" derived from the nervous system, and verbal indicators expressed and derived from language).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] These sometimes mislead us about what is the truth.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Our understanding sometimes lacks *similarity of structure* with what is actually happening.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He sought to train our awareness of abstracting, using techniques he had derived from his study of mathematics and science.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He called this awareness, this goal of his system, "consciousness of abstracting".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] His system included the promotion of attitudes such as "I don't know; let's see," in order that we may better discover or reflect on its realities as revealed by modern science.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Another technique involved becoming inwardly and outwardly quiet, an experience he termed, "silence on the objective levels".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He thought that *certain uses* of the verb "to be", called the "is of identity" and the "is of predication", were faulty in structure, e.g., a statement such as, "Elizabeth is a fool" (said of a person named "Elizabeth" who has done something that we regard as foolish).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] In Korzybski's system, one's assessment of Elizabeth belongs to a higher order of abstraction than Elizabeth herself.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Korzybski's remedy was to *deny* identity; in this example, to be aware continually that "Elizabeth" is *not* what we *call* her.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] We find Elizabeth not in the verbal domain, the world of words, but the nonverbal domain (the two, he said, amount to different orders of abstraction).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] This was expressed by Korzybski's most famous premise, "the map is not the territory".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Note that this premise uses the phrase "is not", a form of "to be"; this and many other examples show that he did not intend to abandon "to be" as such.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] In fact, he said explicitly that there were no structural problems with the verb "to be" when used as an auxiliary verb or when used to state existence or location.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] It was even acceptable at times to use the faulty forms of the verb "to be," as long as one was aware of their structural limitations.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] One day, Korzybski was giving a lecture to a group of students, and he interrupted the lesson suddenly in order to retrieve a packet of biscuits, wrapped in white paper, from his briefcase.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] He muttered that he just had to eat something, and he asked the students on the seats in the front row if they would also like a biscuit.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] "Nice biscuit, don't you think", said Korzybski, while he took a second one.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Then he tore the white paper from the biscuits, in order to reveal the original packaging.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] On it was a big picture of a dog's head and the words "Dog Cookies".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] The students looked at the package, and were shocked.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Two of them wanted to vomit, put their hands in front of their mouths, and ran out of the lecture hall to the toilet.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] "You see", Korzybski remarked, "I have just demonstrated that people don't just eat food, but also words, and that the taste of the former is often outdone by the taste of the latter".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] William Burroughs went to a Korzybski workshop in the autumn of 1939.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] His fellow students—there were 38 in all—included young Samuel I.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Hayakawa (later to become a Republican member of the U.S.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Senate) and Wendell Johnson (founder of the Monster Study).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Korzybski's work had a positive reception from a variety of persons in the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Heinlein named a character after him in his 1940 short story "Blowups Happen".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] E. van Vogt based his novel *The World of Null-A*, published in 1948, on ideas from General Semantics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] On March 8, 1949, fellow science-fiction author L.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Korzybski's ideas influenced philosopher Alan Watts and physicist Fritjof Capra who used his phrase "the map is not the territory" in lectures and writings "The Tao of Physics", 35th Anniversary Edition.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Writer Robert Anton Wilson was also deeply influenced by Korzybski's ideas.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Avant-Garde Situationist artist and author Ralph Rumney used Korzybski's phrase "the map is not the territory" as a title for his autobiography, which was published in 2001.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] The third edition of *Science and Sanity* states that in World War II the United States Army used Korzybski's system to treat battle fatigue in Europe, under the supervision of Dr.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Kelley, who went on to become the psychiatrist in charge of the Nazi war criminals at Nuremberg.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-korzybski] Some of the General Semantics tradition was continued by Samuel I.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In his early career Whitehead wrote primarily on mathematics, logic, and physics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He wrote the three-volume *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913), with his former student Bertrand Russell.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] *Principia Mathematica* is considered one of the twentieth century's most important works in mathematical logic, and placed 23rd in a list of the top 100 English-language nonfiction books of the twentieth century by Modern Library.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Beginning in the late 1910s and early 1920s, Whitehead gradually turned his attention from mathematics to philosophy of science, and finally to metaphysics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He developed a comprehensive metaphysical system which radically departed from most of Western philosophy.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead argued that reality consists of processes rather than material objects, and that processes are best defined by their relations with other processes, thus rejecting the theory that reality is fundamentally constructed by bits of matter that exist independently of one another.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's philosophical works – particularly *Process and Reality* – are regarded as the foundational texts of process philosophy.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Alfred North Whitehead was born in Ramsgate, Kent, England, in 1861.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His father, Alfred Whitehead, became an Anglican minister after being headmaster of Chatham House Academy, a school for boys previously headed by Alfred's father, Thomas Whitehead.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead himself recalled both of them as being very successful schoolmasters, with his grandfather being the more "remarkable" man.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's mother was Maria Sarah Buckmaster.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Her maternal great-grandmother was Jane North (1776–1847), whose maiden surname was given to Whitehead, and several other members of his family over time.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His mother, Maria Buckmaster had eleven siblings.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The son of her brother Thomas, Walter Selby Buckmaster, was twice an Olympics silver medal winner for Polo (1900, 1908) for Britain, and is said to be "one of the finest polo players England has ever produced".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead does not appear to have been close to his mother, although he and Evelyn (full name: Evelyn Ada Maud Rice Willoughby Wade), whom he married in 1890, are recorded in the English Census of 1891 as living with Alfred's mother and father.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Lowe notes that there appears to have been mutual dislike between Whitehead's wife, Evelyn, and his mother, Maria.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Griffin relates how Bertrand Russell, a colleague and collaborator of Whitehead, was a very close friend of Whitehead and of his wife, Evelyn.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Intensity of emotion was encouraged by their avant-garde associates in the turbulent Bloomsbury Group which "discussed aesthetic and philosophical questions in a spirit of agnosticism and were strongly influenced by G.E.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Moore's *Principia Ethica* (1903) and by A.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's and Bertrand Russell's *Principia Mathematica* (1910–13), in the light of which they searched for definitions of the good, the true, and the beautiful".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Alfred's brother Henry became Bishop of Madras and wrote the closely observed ethnographic account *Village Gods of South-India* (Calcutta: Association Press, 1921).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was educated at Sherborne, a prominent English public school, where he excelled in sports and mathematics and was head prefect of his class.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1880, he began attending Trinity College, Cambridge, and studied mathematics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He earned his B.A. from Trinity in 1884, writing his dissertation on James Clerk Maxwell's *A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism*, and graduated as fourth wrangler.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1910, Whitehead resigned his senior lectureship in mathematics at Trinity and moved to London without first obtaining another job.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] After being unemployed for a year, he accepted a position as lecturer in applied mathematics and mechanics at University College London but was passed over a year later for the Goldsmid Chair of Applied Mathematics and Mechanics, a position for which he had hoped to be seriously considered.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1914, Whitehead accepted a position as professor of applied mathematics at the newly chartered Imperial College London, where his old friend Andrew Forsyth had recently been appointed chief professor of mathematics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1918, Whitehead's academic responsibilities began to seriously expand as he accepted a number of high administrative positions within the University of London system (of which Imperial College London was a member at the time).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was able to exert his newfound influence to successfully lobby for a new history of science department, help establish a Bachelor of Science degree (previously only Bachelor of Arts degrees had been offered), and make the school more accessible to less wealthy students.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Toward the end of his time in England, Whitehead turned his attention to philosophy.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Though he had no advanced training in philosophy, his philosophical work soon became highly regarded.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] After publishing *The Concept of Nature* in 1920, he served as president of the Aristotelian Society from 1922 to 1923.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1924, Henry Osborn Taylor invited the 63-year-old Whitehead to join the faculty at Harvard University as a professor of philosophy.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The Whiteheads would spend the rest of their lives in the United States.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] During his time at Harvard, Whitehead produced some of his most important philosophical contributions.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1925, he wrote *Science and the Modern World*, which was immediately hailed as an alternative to the Cartesian dualism then prevalent in popular science.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences that same year.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1926.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Lectures from 1927 to 1928 were published in 1929 as a book named *Process and Reality*, which has been compared to Immanuel Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1890, Whitehead married Evelyn Wade, an Irishwoman raised in France; they had a daughter, Jessie, and two sons, Thomas and Eric.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Thomas followed his father to Harvard in 1931, to teach at the Business School.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Eric died in action at the age of 19, while serving in the Royal Flying Corps during World War I.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] From 1910, the Whiteheads had a cottage in the village of Lockeridge, near Marlborough, Wiltshire; from there he completed *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The Whiteheads remained in the United States after moving to Harvard in 1924.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Alfred retired from Harvard in 1937 and remained in Cambridge, Massachusetts, until his death on 30 December 1947.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The two-volume biography of Whitehead by Victor Lowe is the most definitive presentation of the life of Whitehead.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, many details of Whitehead's life remain obscure because he left no *Nachlass* (personal archive); his family carried out his instructions that all of his papers be destroyed after his death.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Additionally, Whitehead was known for his "almost fanatical belief in the right to privacy," and for writing very few personal letters of the kind that would help to gain insight on his life.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Lucas Jr., the Whitehead Research Project of the Center for Process Studies is currently working on a critical edition of Whitehead's published and unpublished works.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The first volume of the *Edinburgh Critical Edition of the Complete Works of Alfred North Whitehead* was published in 2017 by Paul A.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Bogaard and Jason Bell as *The Harvard Lectures of Alfred North Whitehead, 1924–1925: The Philosophical Presuppositions of Science*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In addition to numerous articles on mathematics, Whitehead wrote three major books on the subject: *A Treatise on Universal Algebra* (1898), *Principia Mathematica* (co-written with Bertrand Russell and published in three volumes between 1910 and 1913), and *An Introduction to Mathematics* (1911).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The former two books were aimed exclusively at professional mathematicians, while the latter book was intended for a larger audience, covering the history of mathematics and its philosophical foundations.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] *Principia Mathematica* in particular is regarded as one of the most important works in mathematical logic of the 20th century.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In *A Treatise on Universal Algebra* (1898), the term *universal algebra* had essentially the same meaning that it has today: the study of algebraic structures themselves, rather than examples ("models") of algebraic structures.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead credits William Rowan Hamilton and Augustus De Morgan as originators of the subject matter, and James Joseph Sylvester with coining the term itself.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] At the time, structures such as Lie algebras and hyperbolic quaternions drew attention to the need to expand algebraic structures beyond the associatively multiplicative class.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In a review Alexander Macfarlane wrote: "The main idea of the work is not unification of the several methods, nor generalization of ordinary algebra so as to include them, but rather the comparative study of their several structures." In a separate review, G.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead, however, had no results of a general nature.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His hope of "form[ing] a uniform method of interpretation of the various algebras" presumably would have been developed in Volume II, had Whitehead completed it.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Further work on the subject was minimal until the early 1930s when Garrett Birkhoff and Øystein Ore began publishing on universal algebras.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead and Russell had thought originally that *Principia Mathematica* would take a year to complete; it ended up taking them ten years.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Despite the initial loss, today there is likely no major academic library in the world that does not hold a copy of *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Unlike Whitehead's previous two books on mathematics, *An Introduction to Mathematics* (1911) was not aimed exclusively at professional mathematicians but was intended for a larger audience.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The book covered the nature of mathematics, its unity and internal structure, and its applicability to nature.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The book can be seen as an attempt to understand the growth in unity and interconnection of mathematics as a whole, as well as an examination of the mutual influence of mathematics and philosophy, language, and physics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Although the book is little-read, in some ways it prefigures certain points of Whitehead's later work in philosophy and metaphysics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead showed a deep concern for educational reform at all levels.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In addition to his numerous individually written works on the subject, Whitehead was appointed by Britain's Prime Minister David Lloyd George as part of a 20-person committee to investigate the educational systems and practices of the UK in 1921 and recommend reform.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's most complete work on education is the 1929 book *The Aims of Education and Other Essays*, which collected numerous essays and addresses by Whitehead on the subject published between 1912 and 1927.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The essay from which *Aims of Education* derived its name was delivered as an address in 1916 when Whitehead was president of the London Branch of the Mathematical Association.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In it, he cautioned against the teaching of what he called "inert ideas" – ideas that are disconnected scraps of information, with no application to real life or culture.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Rather than teach small parts of a large number of subjects, Whitehead advocated teaching a relatively few important concepts that the student could organically link to many different areas of knowledge, discovering their application in actual life.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In order to make this sort of teaching a reality, however, Whitehead pointed to the need to minimize the importance of (or radically alter) standard examinations for school entrance.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead argued that curriculum should be developed specifically for its own students by its own staff, or else risk total stagnation, interrupted only by occasional movements from one group of inert ideas to another.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Above all else in his educational writings, Whitehead emphasized the importance of imagination and the free play of ideas.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's philosophy of education might adequately be summarized in his statement that "knowledge does not keep any better than fish".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In other words, bits of disconnected knowledge are meaningless; all knowledge must find some imaginative application to the students' own lives, or else it becomes useless trivia, and the students themselves become good at parroting facts but not thinking for themselves.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead did not begin his career as a philosopher.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In fact, he never had any formal training in philosophy beyond his undergraduate education.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Early in his life, he showed great interest in and respect for philosophy and metaphysics, but it is evident that he considered himself a rank amateur.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, interest in metaphysics – the philosophical investigation of the nature of the universe and existence – had become unfashionable by the time Whitehead began writing in earnest about it in the 1920s.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The ever-more impressive accomplishments of empirical science had led to a general consensus in academia that the development of comprehensive metaphysical systems was a waste of time because they were not subject to empirical testing.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was unimpressed by this objection.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In the notes of one of his students for a 1927 class, Whitehead was quoted as saying: "Every scientific man in order to preserve his reputation has to say he dislikes metaphysics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] What he means is he dislikes having his metaphysics criticized." In Whitehead's view, scientists and philosophers make metaphysical assumptions about how the universe works all the time, but such assumptions are not easily seen precisely because they remain unexamined and unquestioned.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For this reason, Whitehead regarded metaphysical investigations as essential to both good science and good philosophy.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He also argued that the most basic elements of reality can all be regarded as experiential, indeed that everything is constituted by its experience.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He used the term "experience" very broadly so that even inanimate processes such as electron collisions are said to manifest some degree of experience.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this, he went against Descartes' separation of two different kinds of real existence, either exclusively material or else exclusively mental.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's philosophy was highly original, and soon garnered interest in philosophical circles.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This is not to say that Whitehead's thought was widely accepted or even well understood.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His philosophical work is generally considered to be among the most difficult to understand in all of the Western canon.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Even professional philosophers struggled to follow Whitehead's writings.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It may not be inappropriate to speculate that some fair portion of the respect generally shown to Whitehead by his philosophical peers at the time arose from their sheer bafflement.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, Mathews' frustration with Whitehead's books did not negatively affect his interest.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In fact, there were numerous philosophers and theologians at Chicago's Divinity School who perceived the importance of what Whitehead was doing without fully grasping all of the details and implications.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In 1927, they invited one of America's only Whitehead experts, Henry Nelson Wieman, to Chicago to give a lecture explaining Whitehead's thoughts.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Wieman's lecture was so brilliant that he was promptly hired to the faculty and taught there for twenty years, and for at least thirty years afterwards Chicago's Divinity School was closely associated with Whitehead's thought.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead was convinced that the scientific notion of matter was misleading as a way of describing the ultimate nature of things.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In Whitehead's view, there are a number of problems with this notion of "irreducible brute matter".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] First, it obscures and minimizes the importance of change.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] By thinking of any material thing (like a rock, or a person) as being fundamentally the *same* thing throughout time, with any changes to it being secondary to its "nature", scientific materialism hides the fact that nothing ever stays the same.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, change is fundamental and inescapable; he emphasizes that "all things flow".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In Whitehead's view, then, concepts such as "quality", "matter", and "form" are problematic.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] These "classical" concepts fail to adequately account for change, and overlook the active and experiential nature of the most basic elements of the world.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] They are useful abstractions but are not the world's basic building blocks.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] What is ordinarily conceived of as a single person, for instance, is philosophically described as a continuum of overlapping events.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] After all, people change all the time, if only because they have aged by another second and had some further experience.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] These occasions of experience are logically distinct but are progressively connected in what Whitehead calls a "society" of events.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] By assuming that enduring objects are the most real and fundamental things in the universe, materialists have mistaken the abstract for the concrete (what Whitehead calls the "fallacy of misplaced concreteness").
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] To put it another way, a thing or person is often seen as having a "defining essence" or a "core identity" that is unchanging, and describes what the thing or person *really is*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this way of thinking, things and people are seen as fundamentally the same through time, with any changes being qualitative and secondary to their core identity (e.g., "Mark's hair has turned grey as he has gotten older, but he is still the same person").
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] But in Whitehead's cosmology, the only fundamentally existent things are discrete "occasions of experience" that overlap one another in time and space, and jointly make up the enduring person or thing.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] On the other hand, what ordinary thinking often regards as "the essence of a thing" or "the identity/core of a person" is an abstract generalization of what is regarded as that person or thing's most important or salient features across time.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Identities do not define people; people define identities.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Everything changes from moment to moment and to think of anything as having an "enduring essence" misses the fact that "all things flow," though it is often a useful way of speaking.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead pointed to the limitations of language as one of the main culprits in maintaining a materialistic way of thinking and acknowledged that it may be difficult to ever wholly move past such ideas in everyday speech.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Yet the limitations of everyday living and everyday speech should not prevent people from realizing that "material substances" or "essences" are a convenient generalized description of a continuum of particular, concrete processes.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] No one questions that a ten-year-old person is quite different by the time he or she turns thirty years old, and in many ways is not the same person at all; Whitehead points out that it is not philosophically or ontologically sound to think that a person is the same from one second to the next.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A second problem with materialism is that it obscures the importance of *relations*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It sees every object as distinct and discrete from all other objects.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Each object is simply an inert clump of matter that is only *externally* related to other things.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The idea of matter as primary makes people think of objects as being fundamentally separate in time and space, and not necessarily related to anything.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] But in Whitehead's view, relations take a primary role, perhaps even more important than the relata themselves.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A student taking notes in one of Whitehead's fall 1924 classes wrote that, "Reality applies to *connections*, and only relatively to the things connected.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A real thing is just that which forces the rest of the universe to in some way conform to it; that is to say, if theoretically, a thing made strictly no difference to any other entity (i.e., it was not *related* to any other entity), it could not be said to really exist.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Relations are not secondary to what a thing is; they *are* what the thing is.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] To Whitehead, an entity is not *merely* a sum of its relations, but also a valuation of them and reaction to them.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, creativity is the absolute principle of existence, and every entity (whether it is a human being, a tree, or an electron) has some degree of novelty in how it responds to other entities and is not fully determined by causal or mechanistic laws.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Most entities do not have consciousness.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] As a human being's actions cannot always be predicted, the same can be said of where a tree's roots will grow, or how an electron will move, or whether it will rain tomorrow.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Moreover, the inability to predict an electron's movement (for instance) is not due to faulty understanding or inadequate technology; rather, the fundamental creativity/freedom of all entities means that there will always remain phenomena that are unpredictable.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The other side of creativity/freedom as the absolute principle is that every entity is constrained by the social structure of existence (i.e., its relations); each actual entity must conform to the settled conditions of the world around it.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] But an entity's uniqueness and individuality arise from its own self-determination as to just how it will take account of the world within the limits that have been set for it.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In summary, Whitehead rejects the idea of separate and unchanging bits of matter as the most basic building blocks of reality, in favour of the idea of reality as interrelated events in the process.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Since Whitehead's metaphysics described a universe in which all entities experience, he needed a new way of describing perception that was not limited to living, self-conscious beings.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The term he coined was "prehension," which comes from the Latin *prehensio*, meaning "to seize".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The term is meant to indicate a kind of perception that can be conscious or unconscious, applying to people as well as electrons.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It is also intended to make clear Whitehead's rejection of the theory of *representative* perception, in which the mind only has private ideas about other entities.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, the term "prehension" indicates that the perceiver actually incorporates aspects of the perceived thing into itself.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this way, entities are constituted by their perceptions and relations, rather than being independent of them.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Further, Whitehead regards perception as occurring in two modes, *causal efficacy* (or "physical prehension") and *presentational immediacy* (or "conceptual prehension").
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Presentational immediacy, on the other hand, is what is usually referred to as "pure sense perception", unmediated by any causal or symbolic interpretation, even unconscious interpretation.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In other words, it is pure appearance, which may or may not be delusive (e.g., mistaking an image in a mirror for "the real thing").
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In higher organisms (like people), these two modes of perception combine into what Whitehead terms "symbolic reference", which links appearance with causation in a process that is so automatic that both people and animals have difficulty refraining from it.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] By way of illustration, Whitehead uses the example of a person's encounter with a chair.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] An ordinary person looks up, sees a coloured shape, and immediately infers that it is a chair.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead believed that when asking questions about the basic facts of existence, questions about value and purpose can never be fully escaped.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This is borne out in his thoughts on abiogenesis, or the hypothetical natural process by which life arises from simple organic compounds.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In other words, Whitehead sees life as directed toward the purpose of increasing its own satisfaction.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Without such a goal, he sees the rise of life as totally unintelligible.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, there is no such thing as wholly inert matter.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Instead, all things have some measure of freedom or creativity, however small, which allows them to be at least partly self-directed.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The process philosopher David Ray Griffin coined the term "panexperientialism" (the idea that all entities experience) to describe Whitehead's view, and to distinguish it from panpsychism (the idea that all matter has consciousness).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's idea of God differs from traditional monotheistic notions.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, God is not necessarily tied to religion.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Rather than springing primarily from religious faith, Whitehead saw God as necessary for his metaphysical system.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His system required that an order exist among possibilities, an order that allowed for novelty in the world and provided an aim to all entities.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead posited that these ordered potentials exist in what he called the *primordial nature* of God.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, Whitehead was also interested in religious experience.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This led him to reflect more intensively on what he saw as the second nature of God, the *consequent nature*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead's conception of God as a "dipolar" entity has called for fresh theological thinking.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The primordial nature he described as "the unlimited conceptual realization of the absolute wealth of potentiality" – i.e., the unlimited possibility of the universe.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] This primordial nature is eternal and unchanging, providing entities in the universe with possibilities for realization.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead also calls this primordial aspect "the lure for feeling, the eternal urge of desire," pulling the entities in the universe toward as-yet unrealized possibilities.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] God's consequent nature, on the other hand, is anything but unchanging; it is God's reception of the world's activity.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] As Whitehead puts it, "[God] saves the world as it passes into the immediacy of his own life.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It is the judgment of a tenderness which loses nothing that can be saved." In other words, God saves and cherishes all experiences forever, and those experiences go on to change the way God interacts with the world.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] In this way, God is really changed by what happens in the world and the wider universe, lending the actions of finite creatures an eternal significance.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead thus sees God and the world as fulfilling one another.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He sees entities in the world as fluent and changing things that yearn for a permanence which only God can provide by taking them into God's self, thereafter changing God and affecting the rest of the universe throughout time.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] On the other hand, he sees God as permanent but as deficient in actuality and change: alone, God is merely eternally unrealized possibilities and requires the world to actualize them.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] God gives creatures permanence, while the creatures give God actuality and change.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The above is some of Whitehead's most evocative writing about God, and was powerful enough to inspire the movement known as process theology, a vibrant theological school of thought that continues to thrive today.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, the core of religion was individual.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] While he acknowledged that individuals cannot ever be fully separated from their society, he argued that life is an internal fact for its own sake before it is an external fact relating to others.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] His most famous remark on religion is that "religion is what the individual does with his own solitariness ... and if you are never solitary, you are never religious." Whitehead saw religion as a system of general truths that transformed a person's character.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] He took special care to note that while religion is often a good influence, it is not *necessarily* good – an idea which he called a "dangerous delusion" (e.g., a religion might encourage the violent extermination of a rival religion's adherents).
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] However, while Whitehead saw religion as *beginning* in solitariness, he also saw religion as necessarily expanding beyond the individual.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] Whitehead writes further that each entity "can find no such value till it has merged its individual claim with that of the objective universe.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] The spirit at once surrenders itself to this universal claim and appropriates it for itself." In this way, the individual and universal/social aspects of religion are mutually dependent.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] A connection between the works of William DeWitt Hyde and Whitehead further elucidates this necessary duality of social and individual roles in religious experience.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] For Whitehead, religion served as a kind of bridge between philosophy and the emotions and purposes of a particular society.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p01] It is the task of religion to make philosophy applicable to the everyday lives of ordinary people.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One of the first theologians to attempt to interact with Whitehead's thought was the future Archbishop of Canterbury, William Temple.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In Temple's Gifford Lectures of 1932–1934 (subsequently published as "Nature, Man and God"), Whitehead is one of a number of philosophers of the emergent evolution approach with which Temple interacts.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] However, it was not until the 1970s and 1980s that Whitehead's thought drew much attention outside of a small group of philosophers and theologians, primarily Americans, and even today he is not considered especially influential outside of relatively specialized circles.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Early followers of Whitehead were found primarily at the University of Chicago Divinity School, where Henry Nelson Wieman initiated an interest in Whitehead's work that would last for about thirty years.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Professors such as Wieman, Charles Hartshorne, Bernard Loomer, Bernard Meland, and Daniel Day Williams made Whitehead's philosophy arguably the most important intellectual thread running through the divinity school.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] They taught generations of Whitehead scholars, the most notable of whom is John B.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Although interest in Whitehead has since faded at Chicago's divinity school, Cobb effectively grabbed the torch and planted it firmly in Claremont, California, where he began teaching at Claremont School of Theology in 1958 and founded the Center for Process Studies with David Ray Griffin in 1973.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Largely due to Cobb's influence, today Claremont remains strongly identified with Whitehead's process thought.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] But while Claremont remains the most concentrated hub of Whiteheadian activity, the place where Whitehead's thought currently seems to be growing the most quickly is in China.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In order to address the challenges of modernization and industrialization, China has begun to blend traditions of Taoism, Buddhism, and Confucianism with Whitehead's "constructive post-modern" philosophy in order to create an "ecological civilization".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] To date, the Chinese government has encouraged the building of twenty-three university-based centres for the study of Whitehead's philosophy, and books by process philosophers John Cobb and David Ray Griffin are becoming required reading for Chinese graduate students.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Cobb has attributed China's interest in process philosophy partly to Whitehead's stress on the mutual interdependence of humanity and nature, as well as his emphasis on an educational system that includes the teaching of values rather than simply bare facts.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Overall, however, Whitehead's influence is very difficult to characterize.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In English-speaking countries, his primary works are little-studied outside of Claremont and a select number of liberal graduate-level theology and philosophy programs.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Outside of these circles, his influence is relatively small and diffuse and has tended to come chiefly through the work of his students and admirers rather than Whitehead himself.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Deleuze's and Latour's opinions, however, are minority ones, as Whitehead has not been recognized as particularly influential within the most dominant philosophical schools.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Historically, Whitehead's work has been most influential in the field of American progressive theology.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] The most important early proponent of Whitehead's thought in a theological context was Charles Hartshorne, who spent a semester at Harvard as Whitehead's teaching assistant in 1925, and is widely credited with developing Whitehead's process philosophy into a full-blown process theology.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Other notable process theologians include John B.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Cobb, David Ray Griffin, Marjorie Hewitt Suchocki, C.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Robert Mesle, Roland Faber, and Catherine Keller.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Process theology typically stresses God's relational nature.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Rather than seeing God as impassive or emotionless, process theologians view God as "the fellow sufferer who understands," and as the being who is supremely affected by temporal events.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Hartshorne points out that people would not praise a human ruler who was unaffected by either the joys or sorrows of his followers – so why would this be a praiseworthy quality in God?
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Instead, as the being who is most affected by the world, God is the being who can most appropriately respond to the world.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] However, process theology has been formulated in a wide variety of ways.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Robert Mesle, for instance, advocates a "process naturalism" – i.e., a process theology without God.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In fact, process theology is difficult to define because process theologians are so diverse and transdisciplinary in their views and interests.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Cobb is a process theologian who has also written books on biology and economics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Roland Faber and Catherine Keller integrate Whitehead with poststructuralist, postcolonialist, and feminist theory.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Charles Birch was both a theologian and a geneticist.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Gamwell writes on theology and political theory.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In *Syntheism – Creating God in The Internet Age*, futurologists Alexander Bard and Jan Söderqvist repeatedly credit Whitehead for the process theology they see rising out of the participatory culture expected to dominate the digital era.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Process philosophy is even more difficult to pin down than process theology.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In practice, the two fields cannot be neatly separated.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One philosophical school which has historically had a close relationship with process philosophy is American pragmatism.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead himself thought highly of William James and John Dewey, and acknowledged his indebtedness to them in the preface to *Process and Reality*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Charles Hartshorne (along with Paul Weiss) edited the collected papers of Charles Sanders Peirce, one of the founders of pragmatism.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Noted neopragmatist Richard Rorty was in turn a student of Hartshorne.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Scientists of the early 20th century for whom Whitehead's work has been influential include physical chemist Ilya Prigogine, biologist Conrad Hal Waddington, and geneticists Charles Birch and Sewall Wright.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Henry Murray dedicated his "Explorations in Personality" to Whitehead, a contemporary at Harvard.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In physics, Whitehead's theory of gravitation articulated a view that might perhaps be regarded as dual to Albert Einstein's general relativity.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Yutaka Tanaka suggested that the gravitational constant disagrees with experimental findings, and proposed that Einstein's work does not actually refute Whitehead's formulation.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's view has now been rendered obsolete, with the discovery of gravitational waves, phenomena observed locally that largely violate the kind of local flatness of space that Whitehead assumes.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Consequently, Whitehead's cosmology must be regarded as a local approximation, and his assumption of a uniform spatio-temporal geometry, Minkowskian in particular, as an often-locally-adequate approximation.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] An exact replacement of Whitehead's cosmology would need to admit a Riemannian geometry.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Also, although Whitehead himself gave only secondary consideration to quantum theory, his metaphysics of processes has proved attractive to some physicists in that field.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Henry Stapp and David Bohm are among those whose work has been influenced by Whitehead.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In the 21st century, Whiteheadian thought is still a stimulating influence: Timothy E.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Henning, Adam Scarfe, and Dorion Sagan's *Beyond Mechanism* (2013) and Rupert Sheldrake's *Science Set Free* (2012) are examples of Whiteheadian approaches to biology.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One of the most promising applications of Whitehead's thought in recent years has been in the area of ecological civilization, sustainability, and environmental ethics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] A Theology of Ecology* (1971) was the first single-authored book on environmental ethics.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead is widely known for his influence in education theory.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] His philosophy inspired the formation of the Association for Process Philosophy of Education (APPE), which published eleven volumes of a journal titled *Process Papers* on process philosophy and education from 1996 to 2008.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's theories on education also led to the formation of new modes of learning and new models of teaching.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] One such model is the ANISA model developed by Daniel C.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Jordan, which sought to address a lack of understanding of the nature of people in current education systems.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Another model is the FEELS model developed by Xie Bangxiu and deployed successfully in China.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] "FEELS" stands for five things in curriculum and education: Flexible-goals, Engaged-learner, Embodied-knowledge, Learning-through-interactions, and Supportive-teacher.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's philosophy of education has also found institutional support in Canada, where the University of Saskatchewan created a Process Philosophy Research Unit and sponsored several conferences on process philosophy and education.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Howard Woodhouse at the University of Saskatchewan remains a strong proponent of Whiteheadian education.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] "Beyond the Modern University: Toward a Constructive Postmodern University," (2002) is another text that explores the importance of Whitehead's metaphysics for thinking about higher education.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead has had some influence on the philosophy of business administration and organizational theory.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] This has led in part to a focus on identifying and investigating the effect of temporal events (as opposed to static things) within organizations through an "organization studies" discourse that accommodates a variety of 'weak' and 'strong' process perspectives from a number of philosophers.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Staton have also written recently on the mutual influence of Whitehead and Mary Parker Follett, a pioneer in the fields of organizational theory and organizational behaviour.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Stout and Staton see both Whitehead and Follett as sharing an ontology that "understands becoming as a relational process; difference as being related, yet unique; and the purpose of becoming as harmonizing difference." This connection is further analyzed by Stout and Jeannine M.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Love in *Integrative Process: Follettian Thinking from Ontology to Administration*.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Whitehead's political views sometimes appear to be libertarian without the label.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] On the other hand, many Whitehead scholars read his work as providing a philosophical foundation for the social liberalism of the New Liberal movement that was prominent throughout Whitehead's adult life.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Morris wrote that "... there is good reason for claiming that Whitehead shared the social and political ideals of the new liberals.".
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] However, Whitehead's comment addresses means and methods, not "ideals" or pretexts or excuses.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] Books written by Whitehead, listed by date of publication.
[src:gregory-bateson/alfred-north-whitehead-p02] In addition, the Whitehead Research Project of the Center for Process Studies is currently working on a critical edition of Whitehead's writings, which is set to include notes taken by Whitehead's students during his Harvard classes, correspondence, and corrected editions of his books.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In Palo Alto, California, Bateson and his colleagues developed the double-bind theory of schizophrenia.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's interest in systems theory forms a thread running through his work.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was one of the original members of the core group of the Macy conferences in Cybernetics (1941–1960), and the later set on Group Processes (1954–1960), where he represented the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was interested in the relationship of these fields to epistemology.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] His association with the editor and author Stewart Brand helped widen his influence.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson was born in Grantchester in Cambridgeshire, England, on 9 May 1904.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was the third and youngest son of (Caroline) Beatrice Durham and the distinguished geneticist William Bateson.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was named Gregory after Gregor Mendel, the Austrian monk who founded the modern science of genetics.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The younger Bateson attended Charterhouse School from 1917 to 1921, obtained a Bachelor of Arts in biology at St.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] John's College, Cambridge, in 1925, and continued at Cambridge from 1927 to 1929.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] According to Lipset (1982), Bateson's life was greatly affected by the death of his two brothers.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] John Bateson (1898–1918), the eldest of the three, was killed in World War I.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Martin Bateson (1900–1922), the second brother, was then expected to follow in his father's footsteps as a scientist, but came into conflict with his father over his ambition to become a poet and playwright.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The resulting stress, combined with a disappointment in love, resulted in Martin's public suicide by gunshot under the statue of Anteros in Piccadilly Circus on 22 April 1922, which was John's birthday.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] After this event, which transformed a private family tragedy into a public scandal, the parents' ambitious expectations fell on Gregory.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1928, Bateson lectured in linguistics at the University of Sydney.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] From 1931 to 1937, he was a Fellow of St.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He spent the years before World War II in the South Pacific in New Guinea and Bali doing anthropology.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In the 1940s, he helped extend systems theory and cybernetics to the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Although initially reluctant to join the intelligence services, Bateson served in the OSS during World War II along with dozens of other anthropologists.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was stationed in the same offices as Julia Child (then Julia McWilliams), Paul Cushing Child, and others.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He spent much of the war designing 'black propaganda' radio broadcasts.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was deployed on covert operations in Burma and Thailand, and worked in China, India, and Ceylon as well.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson used his theory of schismogenesis to help foster discord among enemy fighters.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was upset by his wartime experience and disagreed with his wife over whether science should be applied to social planning or used only to foster understanding rather than action.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In Palo Alto, California, Bateson developed the double-bind theory, together with his non-colleagues Donald Jackson, Jay Haley and John H.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Weakland, also known as the *Bateson Project* (1953–1963).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1956, he became a naturalised citizen of the United States.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson was one of the original members of the core group of the Macy conferences in cybernetics (1941–1960), and the later set on Group Processes (1954–1960), where he represented the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In the 1970s, he taught at the Humanistic Psychology Institute in San Francisco, which was renamed the Saybrook University, and in 1972 joined the faculty of Kresge College at the University of California, Santa Cruz.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1976, he was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] California Governor Jerry Brown appointed him to the Regents of the University of California, a position he held until his death, although he resigned from the Special Research Projects committee in 1979 in opposition to the university's work on nuclear weapons.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson spent the last decade of his life developing a "meta-science" of epistemology to bring together the various early forms of systems theory developed in different fields of science.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] From 1936 until 1950, he was married to American cultural anthropologist Margaret Mead.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He applied his knowledge to the war effort before moving to the United States.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson and Mead had a daughter, Mary Catherine Bateson (1939–2021), who also became an anthropologist.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson separated from Mead in 1947, and they were divorced in 1950.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1951, he married Elizabeth "Betty" Sumner, the daughter of the Episcopalian Bishop of Oregon, Walter Taylor Sumner.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] They had a son, John Sumner Bateson (1951–2015), as well as twins who died shortly after birth in 1953.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson and Sumner were divorced in 1957, after which Bateson was married a third time, to therapist and social worker Lois Cammack (born 1928), in 1961.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] They had one daughter, Nora Bateson (born 1968).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson was a lifelong atheist, as his family had been for several generations.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He was a member of William Irwin Thompson's esoteric Lindisfarne Association.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson died on July 4, 1980, at age 76, in the guest house of the San Francisco Zen Center.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The 2014 novel *Euphoria* by Lily King is a fictionalized account of Bateson's relationships with Mead and Reo Fortune in pre-WWII New Guinea.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Where others might see a set of inexplicable details, Bateson perceived simple relationships.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In "From Versailles to Cybernetics," Bateson argues that the history of the twentieth century can be perceived as the history of a malfunctioning relationship.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In his view, the Treaty of Versailles exemplifies a whole pattern of human relationships based on betrayal and hate.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He therefore claims that the Treaty of Versailles and the development of cybernetics—which for him represented the possibility of *improved* relationships—are the only two anthropologically important events of the twentieth century.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's beginning years as an anthropologist were spent floundering, lost without a specific objective in mind.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He began in 1927 with a trip to New Guinea, spurred by his mentor A.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] His goal, as suggested by Haddon, was to explore the effects of contact between the Sepik natives and whites.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Unfortunately for Bateson, his time spent with the Baining of New Guinea was halted and difficult.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The Baining were not particularly accommodating of his research, and he missed out on many communal activities.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] They were also not inclined to share their religious practices with him.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Next, he set out to study the Sulka, belonging to another native population of New Guinea.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Although the Sulka were very different from the Baining and their culture was more easily observed, he felt their culture was dying, which left him dispirited and discouraged.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He experienced more success with the Iatmul people, an indigenous people living along New Guinea's Sepik River.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The observations he made among the Iatmul people allowed him to develop his concept of schismogenesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In his 1936 book *Naven* he defined the term, based on his Iatmul fieldwork, as "a process of differentiation in the norms of individual behaviour resulting from cumulative interaction between individuals" (p.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The book was named after the 'naven' rite, an honorific ceremony among the Iatmul, still continued today, that celebrates first-time cultural achievements.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The ceremony entails behaviours that are otherwise forbidden in everyday social life.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] For example, men and women reverse and exaggerate gender roles; men dress in women's skirts, and women dress in men's attire and ornaments.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Additionally, some women smear mud in the faces of other relatives, beat them with sticks, and hurl bawdy insults.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Mothers may drop to the ground so their celebrated 'child' walks over them.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] And during a male rite, a mother's brother may slide his buttocks down the leg of his honoured sister's son, a complex gesture of masculine birthing, pride, and insult, rarely performed before women, that brings the honoured sister's son to tears.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In short, the behaviour of person X affects person Y, and the reaction of person Y to person X's behaviour will then affect person X's behaviour, which in turn will affect person Y, and so on.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson called this the "vicious circle." He then discerned two models of schismogenesis: symmetrical and complementary.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Symmetrical relationships are those in which the two parties are equals, competitors, such as in sports.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Complementary relationships feature an unequal balance, such as dominance-submission (parent-child), or exhibitionism-spectatorship (performer-audience).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's experiences with the Iatmul led him to publish a book in 1936 titled *Naven: A Survey of the Problems Suggested by a Composite Picture of the Culture of a New Guinea Tribe Drawn from Three Points of View* (Cambridge University Press).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The book proved to be a watershed in anthropology and modern social science.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Until Bateson published *Naven,* most anthropologists assumed a realist approach to studying culture, in which one simply described social reality.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's book argued that this approach was naive, since an anthropologist's account of a culture was always and fundamentally shaped by whatever theory the anthropologist employed to define and analyse the data.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] To think otherwise, stated Bateson, was to be guilty of what Alfred North Whitehead called the "fallacy of misplaced concreteness." There was no singular or self-evident way to understand the Iatmul naven rite.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Instead, Bateson analysed the rite from three unique points of view: sociological, ethological, and eidological.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The book, then, was not a presentation of anthropological analysis but an epistemological account that explored the nature of anthropological analysis itself.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The sociological point of view sought to identify how the ritual helped bring about social integration.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In the 1930s, most anthropologists understood marriage rules to regularly ensure that social groups renewed their alliances.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] But Iatmul, argued Bateson, had contradictory marriage rules.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Marriage, in other words, could not guarantee that a marriage between two clans would at some definite point in the future recur.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Instead, Bateson continued, the naven rite filled this function by regularly ensuring exchanges of food, valuables, and sentiment between mothers' brothers and their sisters' children, or between separate lineages.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Naven, from this angle, held together the different social groups of each village into a unified whole.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The ethological point of view interpreted the ritual in terms of the conventional emotions associated with normative male and female behaviour, which Bateson called ethos.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In Iatmul culture, observed by Bateson, men and women lived different emotional lives.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] For example, women were rather submissive and took delight in the achievements of others; men were fiercely competitive and flamboyant.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] During the ritual, however, men celebrated the achievements of their nieces and nephews while women were given a ritual license to act raucously.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In effect, naven allowed men and women to experience momentarily the emotional lives of each other, thereby to achieve a level of psychological integration.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The third and final point of view, the eidological, was the least successful.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Here Bateson endeavoured to correlate the organisational structure of the naven ceremony with the habitual patterns of Iatmul thought.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Much later, Bateson would harness the very same idea in the development of the double-bind theory of schizophrenia.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Not only did Bateson's approach re-shape fundamentally the anthropological approach to culture, but the naven rite itself has remained a locus classicus in the discipline.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In fact, the meaning of the ritual continues to inspire anthropological analysis.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] From March 1936 until February 1938, Bateson traveled to Bali with his new wife Margaret Mead to study the people of the village of Bajoeng Gede.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Here, Lipset states, "in the short history of ethnographic fieldwork, film was used both on a large scale and as the primary research tool." Bateson took 25,000 photographs of their Balinese subjects.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He discovered that the people of Bajoeng Gede raised their children very unlike children raised in Western societies.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Instead of attention being paid to a child who was displaying a climax of emotion (love or anger), Balinese mothers would ignore them.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson notes, "The child responds to [a mother's] advances with either affection or temper, but the response falls into a vacuum.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In Western cultures, such sequences lead to small climaxes of love or anger, but not so in Bali.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] At the moment when a child throws its arms around the mother's neck or bursts into tears, the mother's attention wanders".
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] This model of stimulation and refusal was also seen in other areas of the culture.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson later described the style of Balinese relations as stasis instead of schismogenesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Their interactions were "muted" and did not follow the schismogenetic process because they did not often escalate competition, dominance, or submission.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1938, Bateson and Mead returned to the Sepik River, and settled in the village of Tambunum, where Bateson had spent three days in the 1920s.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Their aim to replicate the Balinese project on the relationship between child-raising and temperament, and between conventions of the body – such as pose, grimace, holding infants, facial expressions, etc. – reflected wider cultural themes and values.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson snapped some 10,000 black and white photographs, and Mead typed thousands of pages of fieldnotes.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] But Bateson and Mead never published anything substantial from this research.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's encounter with Mead on the Sepik river (Chapter 16) and their life together in Bali (Chapter 17) are described in Mead's autobiography *Blackberry Winter: My Earlier Years* (Angus and Robertson.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Their daughter Catherine's birth in New York on 8 December 1939 is recounted in Chapter 18.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1956 in Palo Alto, Bateson and his colleagues Donald Jackson, Jay Haley, and John Weakland articulated a related theory of schizophrenia stemming from double bind situations.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The double bind refers to a communication paradox described first in families with a schizophrenic member.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The first place where double binds were described (though not named as such) was according to Bateson, in Samuel Butler's *The Way of All Flesh* (a semi-autobiographical novel about Victorian hypocrisy and cover-up).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] No metacommunication is possible – for example, asking which of the two messages is valid or describing the communication as making no sense.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The victim cannot leave the communication field.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Failing to fulfill the contradictory injunctions is punished (for example, by withdrawal of love).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The strange behaviour and speech of schizophrenics were explained by Bateson et al. as an expression of this paradoxical situation, and were seen in fact as an adaptive response, which should be valued as a cathartic and transformative experience.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The double bind was originally presented (probably mainly under the influence of Bateson's psychiatric co-workers) as an explanation of part of the etiology of schizophrenia.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Currently, it is considered to be more important as an example of Bateson's approach to the complexities of communication, which is what he understood it to be.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson writes about how the actual physical changes in the body occur within evolutionary processes.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He describes this through the introduction of the concept of "economics of flexibility".
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In his conclusion he makes seven statements or theoretical positions which may be supported by his ideology.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In fact, the introduction of these stresses can greatly weaken the organism.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] An example that he gives is the sheltering of a sick person from the weather or the fact that someone who works in an office would have a hard time working as a rock climber and vice versa.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The second position states that "the economics of flexibility has a logical structure-each successive demand upon flexibility fractioning the set of available possibilities".
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] This means that theoretically speaking each demand or variable creates a new set of possibilities.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's third conclusion is "that the genotypic change commonly makes demand upon the adjustive ability of the soma".
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] This, he states, is the commonly held belief among biologists although there is no evidence to support the claim.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Added demands are made on the soma by sequential genotypic modifications in the fourth position.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The belief that these organisms will become progressively harmful or dangerous.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] That over time these new "breeds" will become more resistant to the stresses of the environment and changes in genetic traits.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The fifth theoretical position which Bateson believes is supported by his data is that characteristics within an organism that have been modified due to environmental stresses may coincide with genetically determined attributes.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] His sixth position is that it takes less economic flexibility to create somatic change than it does to cause a genotypic modification.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The seventh and final theory he believes to be supported is the idea that, on rare occasions there will be populations whose changes will not be in accordance with the thesis presented within this paper.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] According to Bateson, none of these positions (at the time) could be tested but he called for the creation of a test which could possibly prove or disprove the theoretical positions suggested within.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In his book *Steps to an Ecology of Mind*, Bateson applied cybernetics to the field of ecological anthropology and the concept of homeostasis.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He saw the world as a series of systems containing those of individuals, societies and ecosystems.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Within each system is found competition and dependency.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Each of these systems has adaptive changes which depend upon feedback loops to control balance by changing multiple variables.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson believed that these self-correcting systems were conservative by controlling exponential slippage.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He saw the natural ecological system as innately good as long as it was allowed to maintain homeostasis and that the key unit of survival in evolution was an organism and its environment.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson also viewed that all three systems of the individual, society and ecosystem were all together a part of one supreme cybernetic system that controls everything instead of just interacting systems.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] This supreme cybernetic system is beyond the self of the individual and could be equated to what many people refer to as God, though Bateson referred to it as Mind.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] While Mind is a cybernetic system, it can only be distinguished as a whole and not parts.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson felt Mind was immanent in the messages and pathways of the supreme cybernetic system.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He saw the root of the system collapse as a result of Occidental or Western epistemology.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] According to Bateson, consciousness is the bridge between the cybernetic networks of individuals, society and ecology and the mismatch between the systems due to improper understanding will result in the degradation of the entire supreme cybernetic system or Mind.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson thought that consciousness as developed through Occidental epistemology was at direct odds with Mind.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] At the heart of the matter is scientific hubris.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson argues that Occidental epistemology perpetuates a system of understanding which is purpose or means-to-an-end driven.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Purpose controls attention and narrows perception, thus limiting what comes into consciousness and therefore limiting the amount of wisdom that can be generated from the perception.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Additionally, Occidental epistemology propagates the false notion that man exists outside Mind and this leads man to believe in what Bateson calls the philosophy of control based upon false knowledge.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson presents Occidental epistemology as a method of thinking that leads to a mindset in which man exerts an autocratic rule over all cybernetic systems.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In exerting his autocratic rule man changes the environment to suit him and in doing so he unbalances the natural cybernetic system of controlled competition and mutual dependency.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The purpose-driven accumulation of knowledge ignores the supreme cybernetic system and leads to the eventual breakdown of the entire system.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson claims that man will never be able to control the whole system because it does not operate in a linear fashion and if man creates his own rules for the system, he opens himself up to becoming a slave to the self-made system due to the non-linear nature of cybernetics.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Lastly, man's technological prowess combined with his scientific hubris gives him the potential to irrevocably damage and destroy the supreme cybernetic system, instead of just disrupting the system temporally until the system can self-correct.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson argues for a position of humility and acceptance of the natural cybernetic system instead of scientific arrogance as a solution.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He believes that humility can come about by abandoning the view of operating through consciousness alone.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Consciousness is only one way in which to obtain knowledge and without complete knowledge of the entire cybernetic system disaster is inevitable.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The limited conscious must be combined with the unconscious in a complete synthesis.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Only when thought and emotion are combined in whole is man able to obtain complete knowledge.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] He believed that religion and art are some of the few areas in which a man acts as a whole individual in complete consciousness.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] By acting with this greater wisdom of the supreme cybernetic system as a whole man can change his relationship to Mind from one of schism, in which he is endlessly tied up in constant competition, to one of complementarity.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson argues for a culture that promotes the most general wisdom and is able to flexibly change within the supreme cybernetic system.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The interaction between parts of the mind is triggered by difference...
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Mental process requires collateral energy.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Mental process requires circular (or more complex) chains of determination.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In the mental process the effects of difference are to be regarded as transforms (that is, coded versions) of the difference which preceded them.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The description and classification of these processes of transformation disclose a hierarchy of logical types immanent in the phenomena.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] In 1984, his daughter Mary Catherine Bateson published a joint biography of her parents (Bateson and Margaret Mead).
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] His other daughter the filmmaker Nora Bateson released *An Ecology of Mind*, a documentary that premiered at the Vancouver International Film Festival.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] This film was selected as the audience favourite with the *Morton Marcus Documentary Feature Award* at the 2011 Santa Cruz Film Festival, and honoured with the 2011 *John Culkin Award for Outstanding Praxis in the Field of Media Ecology* by the Media Ecology Association.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The Bateson Idea Group (BIG) initiated a web presence in October 2010.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The group collaborated with the American Society for Cybernetics for a joint meeting in July 2012 at the Asilomar Conference Grounds in California.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] The modern view of artificial intelligence based on social machines has deep links to Bateson's ecological perspectives of intelligence.
[src:gregory-bateson/gregory-bateson] Bateson's work has been a major influence on the emerging interdisciplinary field of social choreography.
